[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ This move characterizes the Najdorf Variation. The idea of the move is two-fold: it controls the b5-square in order to support the b5-push and it also prepares the ...e5 move, which isn't very good immediately in view of 6. Bb5 and 7. Nf5.   In this repertoire I have attempted to cover the most important aspects of the modern treatment of the Najdorf Variation. This means that while I have tried to be as concise as I could - in order to avoid as much as possible the vast amounts of theory the Najdorf has developed - I have paid attention to the most topical lines played nowadays against the Najdorf. This repertoire is not an 'all-inclusive' repertoire as my QGD repertoire - it is impossible to cover everything in the Najdorf. My idea with this repertoire is to provide two things. Firstly, enough theoretical knowledge so that the student is able to confidently play the Najdorf. Secondly, and this is much more important, to help the student develop a feeling for the positions that arise in the Najdorf variation. That is why you will find a lot of textual explanations of the plans and ideas for Black.   The most theoretically heavy chapters in this repertoire that require memorization of forcing lines are the aggressive line with 6. Bg5 and the Sozin  (6 Bc4)  . But from the rest you will see that in the Najdorf a lot depends on correct understanding of the positions and the changes in the pawn structure connected with the d5-square. I have written very extensively about these things in almost all the chapters so I hope that as you progress with learning you will start to recognize what to strive for and what to avoid in Najdorf positions.   I have been a Najdorf player all my life. I started playing it as a kid inspired by the successes of Fischer and Kasparov. The Najdorf brought me many memorable victories  (probably the most important one being my win against GM Korneev in 2007 that secured my third and final GM norm)  and I hope that studying this repertoire will bring you satisfaction in the process and success in practice. Good luck ! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Positional 6. Be2"]
[Black "1. The Positional 6. Be2 - Karpov plan"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2
{ This move was the favorite of Efim Geller and Anatoly Karpov. The move is still popular today as it leads to positional play rather than the wild complications of many other lines in the Najdorf, thus being more to the taste of positional players. }
6... e5
{ The typical Najdorf reaction. Playing  6...e6  would lead to the Classical Scheveningen. }
7. Nb3 { White can also play  7.Nf3.  This option is discussed in lines 6-7. }
7... Be7
{ It is important to start with this move as playing  7...Be6  invites the strong  8.f4 !  Now White has a wide array of options:   8.O-O  - lines 1-5   8.Bg5  - line 8   8.Be3  - lines 9-10   8.g4  - line 11   8.h4  - lines 12-13 }
8. O-O O-O
{ Now White again has a wide choice:   9.Be3  - lines 1-5   9.Kh1  - lines 14-15   9.Qd3  - lines 16-17   9.a4  - lines 18-22   9.Re1  line 23   9.Bg5  - line 24 }
9. Be3
{ Note that  9.Bf3  doesn't have independent value as after  9...Be6  play will transpose to the line   9.a4  Be6  10.Bf3  since White is more or less forced to play  10.a4  here. }
9... Be6 10. Qd2
{ This move is the start of the Karpov System. It is not very popular nowadays, but it is a very deep plan. It consists of the following: White will play a4 to restrict ...b5; then he will put the Rf1 on d1  (the original Karpov plan was to put the rook on c1 and then Bf3 to defend e4, jump Nd5 and when Black takes on d5 the rook on c1 defends the c2-pawn and is ready for the c4-c5 push.)  Then White will further increase the control over d5 with the maneuver Nc1-a2   d3  -b4.   Note that   10.Qd3  Nbd7  transposes to 8. Be3 Be6 9. Qd3 Nbd7. }
10... Nbd7 11. a4 Rc8
{ The start of Black's plan: the first idea is to play ...Nb6-c4, so White prevents that with his next move. }
12. a5 Qc7
{ The second step: the queen moves from the d-file and prepares the knight jump to c5. The good thing about Black's plan is that it is almost exactly the same against all possible white set-ups from this position. }
13. Rfc1
{ This is the original move from the Karpov plan, but Black achieves easy play by playing the usual moves. }
13... Nc5 14. Nxc5 dxc5
{ This structure is very safe. Now White has two options - to jump to d5 or not. Principally speaking, if White jumps to d5, Black takes with the bishop and then puts the Be7 on d6. This ensures good blockade on the dark squares. Then Black will activate his central majority by ...e4 or ...Nd7 and ...f5 with excellent play. If White doesn't jump to d5, then Black will push ...c4 and aim to exchange the dark-squared bishops by ...Bc5. }
15. Nd5
{ This is more ambitious, but Black gets easy play after taking on d5. } 15...
Bxd5 16. exd5 Bd6
{ The bishop is comfortable on d6 and it will become very active after the e-pawn moves forward. }
17. c4 Nd7
{ Black has an excellent position - he will play ...f5 and then most probably ...e4, activating his central and kingside majority. White has problems becoming active on the queenside, meaning he will have to be careful and defensive on the other side of the board. }
