1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Be3 Be6 10. Qd2 Nbd7 11. a4 Rc8 12. a5 Qc7 13. Rfd1 Nc5
{ Black reacts in the same way as after 13. Rfc1, forcing the exchange of knights and opening the d-file. }
14. Nxc5 dxc5 15. Nd5
{ This is the more direct move, but Black obtains excellent play in exactly the same manner as after 13. Rfc1. }
15... Bxd5 16. exd5 Bd6
{ Blocking the d-pawn. The bishop will become very active when Black pushes ...e4. }
17. c4 Nd7
{ With the ideas of ...f5 and then most likely ...e4, opening the bishop and threatening to further push his e- and f-pawns. }
