[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Be3 Be6 10. Qd2 Nbd7 11. a4 Rc8 12. a5 Qc7 13. Rfd1 Nc5 14. Nxc5 dxc5
15. Qe1 Rfd8 { Fighting for the only open file in the position. } 16. Rxd8+
Qxd8
{ An important move. Black wants to push  ...c4  , so it's better to keep the rook behind the pawn instead of the queen. If Black took with the rook  16...Rxd8  , White could have prevented  ...c4  by playing  17.b3  , since then  17...c4  loses the exchange after  18.Bb6.   Now  17.b3  doesn't work because Black simply pushes  17...c4. }
17. f3 c4
{ Now Black wants to play ...Bb4 or exchange the dark-squared bishops with ...Bc5. }
18. Na4 { Preventing both ideas. } 18... Nd7
{ Black's typical reaction to White's Na4, covering both c5 and b6. } 19. Rd1
Qc7
{ With equal play. The queen can come to c6, attacking the Na4 when White will be forced either to retreat or allow further simplifications. }
