[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Positional 6. Be2"]
[Black "5. The Positional 6. Be2 - Karpov plan"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Be3 Be6 10. Qd2 Nbd7 11. a4 Rc8 12. a5 Qc7 13. Bf3
{ A flexible approach, waiting with the rook on f1 to see what Black will do. Luckily, Black just does the same, only this time with a small twist - by using the fact that White removed the bishop from the f1-a6 diagonal, meaning that there is less attack on the a6-pawn, Black is ready to start direct queenside play by pushing ...b5. }
13... Rfd8
{ The last preparatory move. Now wherever White puts the rook from f1 Black can push ...b5. }
14. Rfc1
{ This is more precise. The point is that if the rook is on  d1  , then after  14.Rfd1  b5  15.axb6  Nxb6  16.Rxa6  Nc4  Black will take the pawn on  b2  with a tempo , hitting the rook on  d1. }
14... b5 { Starting active queenside play. Now the variation becomes forced. }
15. axb6 Nxb6 { The knight is heading to c4. } 16. Rxa6 Nc4
{ Black will regain the pawn, he only needs to be precise on his next move. }
17. Qe1 Re8
{ A very important move - the b2-pawn cannot be saved, so Black takes time to move away from the threat of Bb6. }
18. Rb1 Nxb2 { The knight on c3 is hanging and now more forcing play ensues. }
19. Nb5 Qd7 { Attacking the knight on b5. } 20. Nxd6 Bxd6
{ Apparently the only move. } 21. Rxb2 Rc6
{ Black has easy play for the pawn deficit - he simply piles up along the c-file. White's extra c-pawn is a liability, forcing him to stay passive. }
