[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Positional 6. Be2"]
[Black "6. The Positional 6. Be2 - 7. Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nf3
{ This became popular after Magnus Carlsen introduced several fresh ideas in it. However, by now Black already knows how to deal with this move. }
7... Be7 8. Bg5 Be6
{ An important move. As everywhere in the Najdorf where Black pushes  ...e5  control over the d5-square is vital. With  8...Be6  Black establishes control over  d5  before playing  ...Nbd7.   An immediate  8...Nbd7  would allow White to play  9.a4  and  10.Bc4  ,  increasing his control over the d5-square. }
9. Bxf6 { Otherwise Black would connect the knights after ...Nbd7. } 9... Bxf6
10. O-O Be7 { This move prepares ...Nd7 by defending the pawn on d6 first. }
11. Nd5 Nd7
{ From here the knight can go to f6 or b6, thus challenging White's control over the d5-square. In this position everything revolves around the important d5-square ! }
12. Bc4 Rc8
{ Black develops as fast as possible, even waiting a move with castling. The rook move forces White to decide what to do with the bishop on c4 - to put it on b3  (where it can be attacked by a knight from c5)  or to defend it with the queen. }
13. Qe2 Nb6
{ Attacking both the knight and the bishop, forcing the exchange of the knights  (as otherwise Black can take on d5 and force White to recapture with a pawn, something that is very desirable from Black's point of view as it eliminates the weaknesses of the d5-square and the d6-pawn)  . }
14. Nxb6 Qxb6 15. Bb3 O-O { Finishing development. } 16. Rfd1
{ So far this has been played in the game Caruana-Grischuk from the Saint Louis tournament in 2017 and here an improvement over Black's play is  16...Qc5. }
16... Qc5
{ Increasing the pressure on the c-file and freeing the way for the b-pawn. }
17. c3 b5
{ Black starts the usual queenside play by pushing the queenside pawns. He wants to put pressure on either the bishop on b3 by playing ...a5-a4 or the c3-pawn by playing ...b4. }
18. Ne1
{ The knight on  f3  is not a happy piece as it doesn't have good prospects , so often White tries to re-route it to  e3.  This is such an attempt. If White doubles on the d-file with  18.Rd3  then Black can continue with the plan of  18...a5  followed by  ...b4.  The d6-pawn is safely defended so the doubling on the d-file isn't very dangerous. }
18... a5 { Continuing the plan. } 19. Nc2 g6
{ This anticipates White's next move and takes control over the f5-square. It is also based on the fact that if White lands a knight on d5 then Black's counterplay on the f-file will be strong. }
20. Ne3 Bg5 21. Nd5
{ This isn't good in view of Black's next two moves, but otherwise Black will exchange the knight on e3 and put a bishop on c4 with easy equality. }
21... a4 { First Black chases the bishop from b3 from where it controls d5. }
22. Bc2 f5
{ And now he undermines White's centre. The plan is to double on the f-file and increase the pressure. White's beautiful knight is completely harmless in view of Black's active counterplay on both sides of the board. This play around a knight on d5 is typical for the Sveshnikov Sicilian, but it has its place in the Najdorf as well. }
