[Black "7. The Positional 6. Be2 - 7. Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bg5
Be6 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. O-O Be7 11. Nd5 Nd7 12. Bc4 Rc8 13. Bb3 Nc5
{ The knight attacks the bishop that controls d5, thus Black indirectly fights for control over that square. }
14. Re1 { The pawn on e4 was hanging so White had to defend it. } 14... Nxb3
{ Now Black enters a forced sequence leading to an equal endgame. } 15. axb3
Bxd5 16. Qxd5
{ If White takes with the pawn Black will have a wonderful position with a strong majority in the centre and the kingside. After  16.exd5  O-O  he will start pushing  ...f5  and then perhaps  ...Bf6  and  ...e4. }
16... Rxc2
{ This was one of the ideas of ...Rc8, keeping an eye on the c2-pawn. } 17.
Qxb7 O-O
{ Finally getting the king to the safety of the kingside. Please note that taking the pawn on b2 immediately drops the rook to Qc6+ and Qc3. }
18. Qxa6 Rxb2 { Mass simplifications follow and Black is at least equal. } 19.
Reb1 Rxb1+ 20. Rxb1 Qa8
{ The endgame is equal. Black has three ideas here - he can activate the bishop by putting it on b6 via d8  (and at the same time blocking the passed b-pawn)  and he can push either ...d5 or ...f5. White's main problem is that his knight is too far from the ideal d5-square. All this means that Black is at least not worse in this endgame. }
