[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Positional 6. Be2"]
[Black "8. The Positional 6. Be2 - 8. Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Bg5
{ This is similar to the line with 7. Nf3 and Black's reaction is the same one. The only difference here is that White can try to castle queenside but Black has good counterplay there as well. }
8... Be6
{ Again as in the 7. Nf3 line Black hurries to control the d5-square. } 9. Bxf6
Bxf6 10. Qd3 Be7
{ The same idea again - the bishop defends the d6-pawn and allows for the ... Nd7-f6 or b6 maneuver. }
11. O-O-O
{ This is the difference - White can castle queenside, but Black just continues with his plan of control of the d5-square. If White castles kingside then Black continues with the same ...Nd7 and then according to circumstances the knight moves to either f6 or to b6  (with or without the inclusion of ...b5)  . }
11... Nd7 { The most flexible square for the knight. } 12. g3
{ This is White's best attempt. He tries to push f4-f5 and start attack on the kingside.  12.Nd5  is harmless because after  Bxd5  13.Qxd5  Qc7  14.Kb1  O-O  Black's play follows naturally:  ...b5  ,  ...Nb6  ,  ...Rfc8  , maybe  ...a5-a4  etc. , while White's kingside play is nowhere near to be seen. }
12... b5
{ Black continues his queenside play. This secures c4 for the bishop and when the knight comes to b6 it won't block the b-pawn. }
13. f4 Rc8
{ Not only a developing move, but also a move that keeps an eye on the c3-knight. }
14. f5 Bc4 15. Qf3 Bxe2 { Forcing White to take with the knight. } 16. Nxe2
{ If  16.Qxe2  then  16...Rxc3  , which shows the main point of the move  13...Rc8.  This typical Sicilian sacrifice gives Black full compensation and very easy play after  17.bxc3  Nb6.  Black will follow with  ...Nc4  or  ...Na4  ,  ...Qc7  ,  ...O-O  ,  ...Rc8  and so on. }
16... a5 { With a strong initiative on the queenside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Positional 6. Be2"]
[Black "9. The Positional 6. Be2 - 8. Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3
{ This is a flexible move. White develops the last light piece and keeps the option to castle queenside. }
8... Be6
{ The usual move for Black in these structures, keeping an eye on d5. } 9. h4
{ This is the latest idea in this position, introduced by GM Wesley So at the 2018 Olympiad. Moving the h- and g-pawns has become quite common in modern theory. }
9... h5
{ This is the simplest. As we can see from the analysis of the English Attack the move ...h5 is often very useful for Black and here this is also the case as it stops any possible kingside play by White by controlling the g4-square. }
10. Nd5
{ The inclusion of h4 and ...h5 has weakened the g5-square, so White uses this fact to force Black to take on d5. }
10... Bxd5
{ The point is that if Black plays  10...Nbd7  as he does after the immediate 9  Nd5  , then White can take on  e7  and play  Bg5  , awkwardly pinning the knight on  f6  as the bishop cannot be chased away by  ...h6. }
11. exd5 Nbd7
{ Finishing development. Black's plan in these structures is to secure the queenside by playing ...a5 and ...b6 and then concentrate on his kingside and central majority by advancing it in the most appropriate way for the situation at hand. The exchange of the dark-squared bishops is also in Black's favour. }
12. c4 Rc8
{ The c-file is the natural file for the rook from where it also discourages plans with long castling for White. }
13. a4 a5
{ A very important move in all similar positions. It is vital to stop a5 when White would have the clear plan of pushing b4 and c5. The move 13... a5 secures Black's queenside and after a subsequent ...b6 he will have a stronghold on c5 for the knight on d7. The weakened light squares b5 and c6 are difficult to reach for White and even if he somehow manages to put a knight on b5 that knight will be ineffective there. }
14. Nd2 b6
{ Finalizing the defensive set-up on the queenside. Black will continue with ...g6 in order to defend h5 and then castle short. Then his plan will be to organize his kingside play, with possible ideas being: pushing ...f5 and then either ...f4 or ...e4; the knight maneuver ...Ne8-g7-f5; the activation of the bishop via f6. }
