[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Positional 6. Be2"]
[Black "10. The Positional 6. Be2 - 8. Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3
Be6 9. Qd3
{ This has become very popular lately. Note that  9.Nd5  would transpose after  9...Nbd7  (attacking the e4-pawn after having taken control of the b6-square)  10.Qd3.   If White plays  10.Nxe7  (instead of Qd3)  then after  10...Qxe7  the e4-pawn is hanging and  ...d5  is threatened. If White tries to defend against both with  11.Bf3  then  11...O-O  gives Black easy play after he puts the rooks on the c- and d-files.   Another transposition is  9.O-O  O-O  , which transposes to 8  O-O  O-O  9  Be3  Be6  - lines 1-5. }
9... Nbd7
{ It is important not to castle short too early as sometimes this gives White the option to castle to the opposite side. }
10. Nd5 Bxd5
{ Black employs the same strategy as in the line where we had h4 and ...h5 inserted: the centre is fixed now and he can first secure the queenside by ...b6 and ...a5 and then start his kingside and central play. }
11. exd5 Rc8
{ Again discouraging plans that involve long castling. In case of the premature  11...O-O  White has the very dangerous  12.g4 ! }
12. c4 O-O { Black is fully mobilized and will start his usual play. } 13. O-O
Ne8
{ Liberating the way for the f-pawn. Black also threatens to exchange the bishops by ...Bg5, hence White's next move. }
14. Qd2 b6
{ An extremely important move. With his last move, apart from preventing ...Bg5, White threatened Na5, thus fixing Black's queenside. With 14... b6 Black prevents this with a move that is part of his normal defensive set-up on the queenside anyway. }
15. Rac1 a5
{ There it is, the queenside is secure and Black can now start pushing the f-pawn. }
16. Na1
{ White's idea is to transfer the knight via c2 and a3 to b5, but even when it arrives there it won't have much to do. }
16... f5 17. f3 f4
{ This is a great idea only because Black can exchange the dark-squared bishops on the next move. Otherwise ...f4 would just have left Black with a bad dark-squared bishop. }
18. Bf2 Bh4
{ Black has great play on the kingside with the knights coming to c5, f6 or even f5  (via g7)  . We are following Georgiadis - Mamedyarov, Biel, 2018. }
*

