[White "The Positional 6. Be2"]
[Black "12. The Positional 6. Be2 - 8. h4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. h4
{ This is another very recent attempt. } 8... Be6
{ Black continues along the usual lines. Here  8...h5  (like in the line 8 Be3 Be6 9 h4 h5)  wouldn't be ideal as White can play  9.Bg5  in one move. }
9. f4 exf4
{ The threat was f5 so Black eliminates it and gains tempo to finish development. }
10. Bxf4 Nc6
{ The knight is well placed on c6 as it can go to b4 and support ...d5. With fully developed light pieces Black now threatens to push ...d5. }
11. Qd3 Nb4
{ It is important to understand that with his last move White prevented the natural  11...d5  in view of  12.Qg3.  Hence the knight move , attacking the queen and helping the pawn push. }
12. Qd2 d5 { Now everything is smooth sailing for Black. } 13. a3 d4
{ Of course, there are other moves, but this one suffices. } 14. axb4 dxc3 15.
bxc3 Nxe4 16. Qe3 Nf6 17. Rd1 Qc8
{ With a complex middlegame position in which Black has the advantage of the safer king. }
