[White "The Positional 6. Be2"]
[Black "13. The Positional 6. Be2 - 8. h4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. h4
Be6 9. f4 exf4 10. Bxf4 Nc6 11. Qd2 d5
{ This pawn push in the Sicilian, if correct, almost always solves all problems. }
12. O-O-O dxe4 13. Qe3 Qc8
{ The only move, but one that is enough. Black will castle short and will have good play in an open position with all his pieces well-developed. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Positional 6. Be2"]
[Black "14. The Positional 6. Be2 - 9. Kh1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Kh1
{ This is a very cunning waiting move. The move was widely popular in the 1990s and is still played today. White is anticipating both Black's most natural moves, 9... Be6 and 9... b5 by making a useful move.   9...Be6  is then met by  10.f4  and the king is safe in the corner and the bishop on  c1  comes to  f4  in one move when Black takes on  f4.   9...b5  is met by  10.a4  and after  10...b4  11.Nd5  White has initiative. }
9... b6
{ Black is also cunning in his reply. If ...b5 doesn't work then ...b6 does, as it prepares the fianchetto of the bishop on c8 without allowing the undermining move a4. }
10. Be3 Bb7 { Attacking e4, so White's next is forced. } 11. f3 b5
{ Black expands on the queenside before White can clamp down on it by playing a4. Now if allowed Black will play ...Nbd7-b6 and will push ...d5, so White must hurry. }
12. a4 b4
{ This forces the knight to go forward and then a pawn will arrive on d5, which usually favours Black. }
13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nd7
{ Finishing development and taking control over the dark squares on the queenside. Strategically Black still wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops, but in view of the more dynamic situation on the queenside he cannot concentrate on pushing his kingside and central majority. Instead he will concentrate on controlling the dark squares on the queenside. }
15. c3
{ White must open up the queenside as all his pieces are looking in that direction. }
15... bxc3 16. bxc3 Bg5
{ The exchange of dark-squared bishops is good for Black - he will either get rid of the passive bishop and exchange his opponent's active one, or will get an active bishop on g5 that controls the very important c1-square, preventing White from using the c-file in order to push c5. }
17. Bf2
{ Taking on g5 is better for Black, as he has the eternal c5-square at his disposal, the stronger bishop  (it will go to c8 and then f5 or d7 as it isn't limited by its own pawns)  and the better pawn structure. }
17... Qc7 { Connecting the rooks and increasing his queenside presence. } 18.
c4 a5 { Fixing the queenside and aiming to activate the b7-bishop via a6. } 19.
c5
{ The only chance for White, before Black is fully mobilized in the centre. }
19... Nxc5 { Liberating d7 for the queen after White pushes d6. } 20. Nxc5 dxc5
21. d6 Qd7 { Blocking the pawn and also eyeing a4. } 22. Bxc5 Bc6
{ The attack on a4 ties down White's pieces. The d6-pawn isn't going anywhere and Black has easy play with the remaining pieces. }
