[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Kh1 b6 10. f3
{ White can start with  10.a4  but after  10...Bb7  11.f3  Nc6  we have a transposition. }
10... Bb7 { Now Black would like to push ...b5 and expand on the queenside. }
11. a4
{ If  11.Be3  then after  11...b5  we have a transposition to 10  Be3  Bb7  11  f3  b5  - line 14. }
11... Nc6
{ With his last move White weakened the b4-square, so the knight aims to get there. From b4 it will also support the d5-push. }
12. Bg5
{ White is also fighting for the d5-square by attacking a piece that controls it. }
12... Nb4
{ Adding the other knight to the fight for control of the d5-square. } 13. Nb1
{ White is trying to harass the strong knight on b4. } 13... a5
{ Black secures a safe retreat for the Nb4 and fixes the queenside. The immediate threat is ... d5 and if the centre is opened then the weakness on b5 won't be felt because of Black's activity. }
14. c3 Na6
{ Of course Black keeps the long diagonal open as he attempts to push ...d5. }
15. c4 { Otherwise Black will push ...d5. } 15... Nh5
{ Exchanging the dark-squared bishop is strategically very favourable for Black as his bishop is passive. Now White will either exchange on e7 and create a lot of dark-squared weaknesses in his camp or will allow the Be7 to become active after ...Bg5 or ...Bh4. In both cases Black has excellent play. }
