1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Qd3 { White defends the e4-pawn and prepares the Nd5 jump. } 9... Be6
{ The usual development. } 10. Bd2
{ The latest twist. White eyes the a5-square after the  Nc3  jumps to  d5.  The more natural looking  10.Be3  after  10...Nbd7  11.Nd5  Bxd5  12.exd5  Rc8  13.c4  Ne8  transposes to the line 8  Be3  Be6  9  Qd3  Nbd7  - line 10. }
10... Nbd7 { Finishing development. } 11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. exd5 a5
{ Black is careful not to allow the blocking move Na5. 12... a5 threatens ...a4 so it practically forces White's response. }
13. a4 b6
{ Solidifying the queenside. Black will play ...Nc5 next and then he will start his own play on the other side. }
14. c4 Nc5 15. Nxc5 bxc5
{ Black is at least equal - he can control the b-file with ...Rb8 and has a pawn majority in the centre and the kingside which he can start to prepare for advance. White's bishop pair is harmless in this relatively closed position. }
