1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. a4 { A useful move, limiting Black's queenside play. } 9... Be6 10. Bf3
{ The modern treatment. The bishop on f3 increases control over the d5-square and White's plan is to play Re1 and then maneuver Nd2-f1-e3 when the knight will control d5 and f5. In that position the Bf3 would be very useful adding extra protection to the e4-pawn. }
10... Nbd7
{ Black finishes development in the usual way and is ready for the middlegame. }
11. Be3
{ This move prevents Black's powerful idea of ...Qb8 followed by rerouting the e7-bishop  (as seen in line 22)  by planning Qd2 and Rd1, hitting the d6-pawn - this ties the e7-bishop to the defense of the d6-pawn. }
11... Qc7
{ With the bishop forced to stay on e7  (in view of Qd2 and Rd1)  Black connects the rooks and takes control over the c-file. }
12. a5 b5 { Black immediately starts queenside play. } 13. axb6 Nxb6
{ Threatening ...Nc4, so White's next move is forced. } 14. Na5 Nc4
{ This exchange opens the files on the queenside. } 15. Nxc4 Bxc4 16. Re1 Rfb8
{ With great play on the queenside. If necessary the a-pawn can also be thrown into the mix by advancing to a5 or even a4. }
