1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. a4 Be6 10. Bf3 Nbd7 11. Be3 Qc7 12. Re1 Rfc8
{ Black keeps the rook on a8 so that the pawn on a6 has extra protection when he manages to play ...b5, as in the line when White plays a5. }
13. h3
{ If White pushes  13.a5  then Black replies with  13...b5  , just as in the line after 12  a5. }
13... h6
{ Black is making a useful move and waits for White's plans. Curiously, White is short of useful moves:   if  14.a5  then  14...b5  ,   if  14.Qd2  then  14...Nb6  , threatening  ...Nc4.  And if White tries to relocate the Nb3 then Black can return to the idea of ...Qb8 and ... Bd8. }
14. Nc1 { With the idea of N1e2-g3. } 14... Bd8
{ Since the access of the Ra1 to d1 has been blocked, Black uses the moment to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
15. N1e2 Qb8 { Making space for the bishop. } 16. Ng3 Ba5
{ With excellent counterplay for Black. } *

