1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. a4 Be6 10. f4
{ This is the old move, but it is harmless. I give the following analysis for better understanding of the positions with a pawn on e4 vs a pawn on d6. }
10... exf4
{ This capture liberates the e5-square for the Nb8. In general, these positions with a pawn on e4 versus a pawn on d6 are very comfortable for Black as he can establish an eternal knight on e5. His other strategical aim is to exchange the dark squared bishops. In this concrete line however Black has the even more straightforward plan of quickly pushing ...d5. }
11. Bxf4 Nc6 12. Kh1 d5
{ Playing ...Ne5 is possible, but this concrete move solves all Black's problems by eliminating the only weakness. }
13. e5
{ The only way to try something, but the e- and d-pawn will soon be exchanged anyway. }
13... Nd7 { Now White cannot defend the e5-pawn. } 14. Nxd5 Ndxe5 15. Nxe7+
Qxe7
{ This position is very good for Black. His excellently placed pieces control the centre. The knight on e5 dominates the bishop on e2, thus making White's bishop pair irrelevant. }
