1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Re1 Be6 10. Bf1
{ This is a plan that isn't popular anymore. White defends the e4-pawn and wants to jump to  d5  , but this gives him nothing. Note that  10.Bf3  would transpose to  (9 a4 Be6 10 Bf3 Nbd7 11 Re1 Qb8, line 22)  after  10...Nbd7  11.a4  Qb8  !. }
10... Nbd7 { Black has finished his development. } 11. Nd5 Nxd5
{ When possible it is preferable to keep the bishop pair, even though in this case taking with the bishop was fine. }
12. exd5 Bf5 13. a4 Rc8 { Hitting c2. } 14. c3 Bg6
{ Even though there is nothing wrong with  14...a5  , securing the queenside , this ambitious move that liberates the path for the f-pawn shows that Black can even allow  a5  since his counterplay in the centre and kingside is fast enough. Another reason for this is that White's pieces are far from ideally placed for successful queenside advance. }
15. a5 f5 { Now Black will continue with ...Nf6 or ...Bg5. } 16. f4
{ Trying to stop Black's expansion. } 16... Nf6
{ A nice pawn sacrifice after which Black gets tremendous compensation, for example: }
17. fxe5 dxe5 18. Rxe5 Bd6 19. Re1 Ng4 { With a winning attack. } *

