1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Bg5
{ This is harmless as compared to the 8. Bg5 line White doesn't even have the option to castle long. }
9... Be6
{ Since the move Bg5 is a fight for the d5-square, Black reacts in the same way as after 8. Bg5 - by controlling the d5-square and preparing ...Nbd7. }
10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nd5 Bg5 { The bishop is active on g5. } 12. Qd3 Nd7
{ A flexible square for the knight. It also keeps the c-file free for the ...Rc8-c6 maneuver in case the d6-pawn needs protection. }
13. Rad1 Rc8 14. c3 Kh8
{ The position resembles some lines of the Sveshnikov Sicilian and Black's counterplay is the same as there - Black wants to open the f-file by pushing ...f5. His only dilemma is whether he wants to do that by playing ...g6 first  (when he has the option to retake ...gxf5 if White takes on f5)  or not. This is mostly a matter of taste, as in both cases Black has excellent play. }
