[White "The Sozin 6. Bc4"]
[Black "25. The Sozin 6. Bc4 - 9. f5 mainline"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4
{ This was Fischer's favourite, but recently it has become more rare. Still, it is a dangerous variation and Black can be quickly blown off the board if he mixes up his lines. }
6... e6 { The natural move, blunting the active bishop on c4. } 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8.
f4
{ Traditionally this has been the main move, but White's most recent attempts have been connected with putting the bishop on g5 first. }
8... Nc5
{ Black always plays this move and now White is at a crossroads as he has three main options at his disposal. }
9. f5
{ If White plays  9.Qf3  then after  9...Be7  10.Be3  Qc7  sooner rather than later he will play  f5  , thus transposing to the lines after 9  f5. }
9... Be7 { As usual, Black tries to finish development of the kingside first. }
10. Qf3 { This keeps the option of long castling open. } 10... O-O 11. Be3 Qc7
{ The most flexible move, keeping all options open - to push ...e5, ...b5 or play ...Bd7. }
12. O-O-O { The most aggressive, but this favours Black. } 12... b5
{ Black's attack is so much faster here. The immediate threat is ...b4, when the pawn on e4 will fall. }
13. fxe6 fxe6 14. Qh3 Nxb3+
{ Eliminating the important bishop also reduces the pressure on e6. } 15. axb3
b4
{ Now White is obliged to take on e6 and after a forced sequence a better endgame for Black occurs. }
16. Nxe6 Qa5
{ The threats are many: ...Qa1, ...bxc3, ...Qe5, so White has an only move not to lose immediately. }
17. Nd5 Nxd5
{ The knight had to be taken. After White recaptures Black checks on a1 and picks up the b2-pawn. }
18. exd5 Qa1+ 19. Kd2 Qxb2
{ Now Black wants to play ...Bf6 with a devastating attack, so White again has just one move that doesn't lose. }
20. Bd4 Qxd4+ { The only move for Black too, forcing a favourable endgame. }
21. Nxd4 Bxh3 22. gxh3 Rf2+
{ Activating the rook before the bishop comes out to the dominating position on f6. }
23. Ke3 Raf8
{ Now the threat is ...Bg5 or even ...Bd8-b6. White is probably lost here. } *

