1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8. f4
Nc5 9. f5 Be7 10. Qf3 O-O 11. Be3 Qc7 12. O-O { This is the most sensible. }
12... b5
{ However, after this move Black obtains the typical Sicilian initiative when White has problems keeping his centre under control. The move 12... b5 introduces the threats of ...b4 and ...Bb7. }
13. a3
{ Taking on  e6  is good for Black as after  13.fxe6  fxe6  14.Qh3  he can take the bishop with  14...Nxb3  and then push  ...e5  and  ...b4. }
13... e5
{ This fixes the e4-pawn and is played the exact moment when Black can take on b3 on the next move and follow up with ...Bb7, thus keeping control over the vital d5-square. }
14. Nde2 Nxb3 15. cxb3 Bb7
{ Black has a very comfortable position here - he will continue with ...a5 and ...b4, fighting for increased control over the d5-square, with the idea to eventually push ...d5. }
