Nc5 9. f5 Be7 10. Qf3 O-O 11. Be3 Qc7 12. g4
{ This is another aggressive attempt, but one that fails to a nice combination. }
12... b5
{ Not just an automatic move, but one that prepares the following combination as it liberates the b7-square for the bishop. }
13. g5 Nfxe4 { This is possible only because Black can follow up with ...Bb7. }
14. Nxe4 Bb7
{ White's position is falling apart. He can try various moves, but against all Black emerges on top. }
15. fxe6 { This is the most resilient. } 15... Bxe4
{ Black wins material now but he needs to be a little careful about his kingside. }
16. exf7+ Kh8 17. Qh5 Nxb3 { Eliminating the annoying bishop is always nice. }
18. axb3 Bg6
{ Solidifying the kingside. Black will take on f7 and will have a good advantage in view of his bishop pair in an open position. }
