1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8. f4
Nc5 9. f5 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Qf3 Bd7
{ Black finishes development and remains flexible - he can choose the best moment to take on b3 and push ...e5 and ...b5. }
12. g4
{ The most aggressive approach , but not a very good one. After a move like  12.Be3  Black is ready to push  12...b5. }
12... e5
{ When the opponent has started a wing attack it is time to counter in the centre. }
13. Nde2 Bc6 { Hitting the e4-pawn. } 14. Ng3
{ If  14.Bd5  then  14...Ncxe4  and if  15.Bxc6  then  15...Nxc3  followed by  16...bxc6. }
14... Nxb3
{ Eliminating the piece that controls d5, thus allowing Black to push ...d5 and obtain an advantage. }
15. axb3 d5
{ With a clear advantage to Black - White doesn't have an attack and the only thing he managed was to weaken his king. Note the monster unopposed bishop on c6 that makes the whole difference. }
