[White "The Sozin 6. Bc4"]
[Black "31. The Sozin 6. Bc4 - 7. O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O
{ This is a major alternative, aimed at avoiding the line 7. Bb3 Nbd7.   Now  7...Nbd7  is bad since White can play  8.Re1  ,  not wasting time on Bb3 and preparing various sacrifices on e6 or d5. However, with precise move-order Black can still steer the game back to the main line and the plan with ...Nbd7-c5. }
7... Be7
{ White's castling rules out plans with early g4, so Black makes sure he castles, thus securing his king, before playing the usual ...Nbd7-c5 maneuver. }
8. Bb3
{ If White persists in keeping the bishop on c4, after castling Black may consider pushing ...d5. }
8... O-O
{ With the king safe Black can now decide how to continue his development. } 9.
f4
{ The typical Sozin plan: White wants to push f5 in order to weaken d5 and open the diagonal for the bishop on b3. }
9... Nbd7
{ After tucking the king away Black returns to the plan of ...Nbd7-c5. } 10. f5
Nc5
{ And now we have a transposition to the main line after 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8. f4 Nc5 9. f5 Be7 10. O-O O-O: line 28-30. }
