[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Sozin 6. Bc4"]
[Black "32. The Sozin 6. Bc4 - 8. O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8.
O-O Nc5
{ Once Black establishes a knight on c5 he is safe against sacrifices on e6 and can finish development without major disturbances. }
9. Re1
{ This is a rare plan, but it has been played by strong players, so it needs to be investigated. }
9... Be7 { Finishing development of the kingside. } 10. f4 O-O
{ If White now doesn't push e5 Black will play ...Qc7, ...b5 and ...Bb7. } 11.
e5 dxe5
{ This capture ensures that Black will have the better structure, as the pawn on e5 will be without support. Still, this pawn offers White some attacking prospects, so Black will need to be careful as he still needs to finish the development of his queenside. }
12. fxe5 Nxb3
{ Eliminating the dangerous bishop, thus reducing White's control over d5 and enabling Black's knight on f6 to go there. }
13. axb3 Nd5
{ Black would like to exchange more pieces as then White's attacking potential will disappear and Black will have a strategically winning position with the pair of bishops and a better pawn structure. }
14. Kh1 Nxc3
{ Exchanges favour Black, so he gladly takes on c3, at the same time gaining time for the development of the bishop on c8. }
15. bxc3 Bd7
{ Black finishes development but White still has some activity thanks to the strong knight on d4 and the space-grabbing pawn on e5. }
16. Bf4 f5
{ This is the simplest. Since White was threatening Qg4, Re3-g3, Black would have been forced to play ...f5 anyway. }
17. exf6 Bxf6
{ Black's pair of bishops compensates for the weak pawn on e6. But Black isn't in any danger here as he can take on d4 next and play ...Bc6 and ...Qd5, completely equalizing in a position of opposite-coloured bishops. Otherwise Black can play ...Qb6 and ...Rad8. }
