[White "The Sozin 6. Bc4"]
[Black "34. The Sozin 6. Bc4 - 8. O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8.
O-O Nc5 9. Qe1
{ This is an odd-looking move very recently tried by Vocaturo against Vachier-Lagrave. The idea is to liberate d1 for the rook and also support the e5-push. It's not very dangerous, but it's strange and it may get some followers, so I analyze it here. }
9... Be7
{ Since White isn't threatening anything Black continues with development. }
10. Bg5 h6 { Chasing away the bishop is useful as it can be locked in on g3. }
11. Bh4 g5
{ It is rare for Black to play like this in the Sozin, but White's slow play allows him to show some aggression himself. }
12. Bg3 e5
{ Black locks in the bishop on g3, eliminates the e5-push forever and can take on b3 in order to decrease White's control over d5. }
13. Nf3
{ If the knight went to  f5  after the exchange there Black would win the f5-pawn:  13.Nf5  Bxf5  14.exf5  Qd7. }
13... Nxb3 { Fighting for the light squares. First the bishop is eliminated. }
14. axb3 Be6
{ And now the unopposed bishop arrives to e6 from where it controls d5. Black is already slightly better as White is completely devoid of active play while Black can try ...Nh5 and ...f5 as Vachier-Lagrave did in the aforementioned game. }
