1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8.
Bg5 { Lately this plan has been the choice of the Sozin practitioners. } 8...
Nc5 9. O-O Be7 { Black continues along normal lines. } 10. Re1
{ This plan has a solid foundation and it has been used frequently by GM Sergey Rublevsky. After it was established that White's more direct and sacrificial attempts can successfully be parried, White players started searching for alternatives and currently this plan seems to offer them the most. }
10... O-O 11. f4 h6
{ In this line it is very useful to chase the bishop to an undefended square. Additionally, in some lines the h7-square can be a good one for the knight on f6. }
12. Bh4 Qd7
{ Black has many options here, but this cunning move is aimed against White's main threat of e5. It also prepares ...b5. }
13. e5 dxe5 { Black must take first before moving the knight on d5. } 14. fxe5
Nd5
{ Now we see the point behind 11... h6 and 12... Qd7 - the bishop on h4 is hanging and if White takes on d5 with the knight the queen is not attacked  (as she would have been on c7)  , and when White takes on e7 Black can take on c3 first before recapturing the bishop on e7. }
15. Bxe7 Nxc3 { Winning a tempo first before taking on e7. } 16. bxc3 Qxe7 17.
Re3 b5
{ Black is better here - he has the much better structure and his pieces will soon be excellently developed. }
