1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8.
Bg5 Nc5 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. f4 h6 12. Bh4 Qd7 13. Bf2
{ Since the direct 13. e5 doesn't work, White prepares it by removing the bishop from the vulnerable position on h4. }
13... Qc7
{ The queen did her job on d7, now she moves to c7, again anticipating e5, in which case Black will take and move the knight to the comfortable square on d7. Black also wants to play ...b5. }
14. a3
{ Since he has no direct active possibilities, White tries to preserve the bishop on b3. }
14... b5
{ The natural move, preparing ... Bb7. An alternative plan is to take the bishop, after which White will take with the c-pawn, opening the c-file. Then Black should play ...e5 aiming for simplifications after Nf5, ...Bxf5 followed by ...exf4. }
15. Ba2 Bb7
{ With very comfortable middlegame position for Black. He will put the rooks on e8 and c8 and possibly play ...Na4 to start his queenside play. }
