[White "The Sozin 6. Bc4"]
[Black "37. The Sozin 6. Bc4 - 8. Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8.
Bg5 Nc5 9. f4 { This is a more aggressive treatment. } 9... Be7
{ As usual Black calmly finishes development. } 10. Qf3 Qc7
{ Always a useful move, covering e5 and preparing ...b5, in order to have ...Bb7 in case White plays e5. }
11. O-O-O O-O
{ Both sides finished development and now will start their attacks. Black is in fact much better here as his attack is faster because after ...b5 the immediate threat is ...b4, hitting the knight that defends the central pawn on e4. This threat forces White on the defensive. }
12. Rhe1 { The best try. } 12... b5 { Black continues with his direct play. }
13. Bd5
{ An interesting attempt. Otherwise Black pushes ...b4 or prepares it by ...Rb8. }
13... Nxd5
{ Taking with pawn gives White initiative after he takes on f6 and d5. Now Black stabilizes the position in the centre. }
14. exd5 Bxg5 { Removing White's f-pawn in order to push ...e5. } 15. fxg5 e5
{ Black stabilizes the centre and now he can open the f-file for his own purposes. }
16. Nc6 f6
{ With excellent play for Black as all his pieces are well placed. The knight on c6 only looks good while in fact is rather useless. }
17. Rf1 f5
{ White manages to prevent the opening of the f-file, but now Black obtains two mobile central pawns and has great prospects. }
