[White "The Sozin 6. Bc4"]
[Black "39. The Sozin 6. Bc4 - 9. O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8. f4
Nc5 9. O-O Nfxe4
{ Black can and should take the pawn, but he must absolutely know the following forcing lines. This line is the most forcing one in the whole Sozin Attack. }
10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. f5 e5 { Black tries to keep the centre closed. } 12. Qh5 d5
{ Shutting the diagonal for the bishop. Now White must sacrifice material if he is to justify his aggressive opening play. }
13. Re1 Qc7
{ White was threatening to take on e4, so with the queen move Black defends f7, so that now he can recapture on e4 in case White takes the knight. }
14. Bxd5 Nf6
{ The knight escapes with a tempo and White is forced to sacrifice a piece as if the queen retreats Black develops with ...Be7. }
15. Bxf7+ Qxf7 16. Rxe5+ Be7
{ Both last moves were forced. What follows is more or less forced, and Black must play very precisely. If he does he will emerge with an advantage as he manages to keep the extra piece. }
17. Qe2 Kf8 { Removing the king from the pin. } 18. Bg5 Bd7
{ Finishing development and liberating the 8th rank for the rook so that it can come to the e-file to defend the bishop if required. }
19. Ne6+ Bxe6 { The only move, as White was also threatening Nc7. } 20. Rxe6 h6
{ This doesn't only chase away the bishop, but it also opens a luft on h7 for the king. }
21. Bh4 Bc5+
{ Gaining tempo so that the king can run towards h7, since otherwise the bishop on e7 was hanging. }
22. Kh1 Kg8
{ Black is one step away from happiness, so with his next White tries to prevent ...Kh7. }
23. Rd1 Bf8
{ While it was possible to play  23...Kh7  , in that case White would have taken on  f6  and played  Rd5  , playing for domination. With the consolidating bishop move Black makes sure the e7-square is under control and prepares  ...Kh7  or simply  ...Rc8.  White now further forces the play. }
24. Bxf6 gxf6 25. Qg4+ Qg7
{ Gaining tempo so that the king can finally escape to h7. } 26. Qd4 Kh7
{ Black can already breathe more easily as he's ready to create a threat of his own: ...Rg8. }
27. Qxf6 Rg8
{ Now the queens will be exchanged and Black has excellent winning chances in the following endgame. }
28. Qxg7+ Rxg7
{ White's kingside pawns aren't a threat since Black's king is in front of them to stop them while creating a passed pawn on the queenside is a difficult task for White. Black will consolidate with ...Rc8 and then will start to seek exchanges or attack White's pawns. }
