1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8. f4
Nc5 9. O-O Nfxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. f5 e5 12. Qh5 d5 13. Re1 Qc7 14. Bxd5 Nf6
15. Bxf7+ Qxf7 16. Rxe5+ Be7 17. Qe2 Kf8 18. Bg5 Bd7 19. Re1 Re8
{ It may be tempting to move the bishop, but the rook move prepares it better. Now after the bishop moves more exchanges will follow. }
20. Kh1 h6
{ Again this very useful move, the idea is to open a luft on h7 for the king. }
21. Bh4 Bd6 { Forcing further exchanges. } 22. Bxf6
{ If White takes on e8 Black would take with the knight, so White takes on f6 first. }
22... gxf6 23. Ne6+ Bxe6 { Eliminating White's last light piece. } 24. fxe6 Qg6
{ It is important for the queen to stay on the kingside in order to protect the king. }
25. Rd5 Be7
{ Safely blockading the passed pawn and finally securing the position of the king. Now Black can play ...Rg8 and slowly untangle. With precise play this position should be winning for Black. }
