[Black "41. The Sozin 6. Bc4 - 9. e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8. f4
Nc5 9. e5 Nfd7
{ This is the safer move compared to  9...dxe5  since it keeps the f-file closed. }
10. exd6 Nf6
{ Taking the pawn with the bishop would have been met by Nf5, so Black returns to f6 first and will then take on d6. }
11. Be3 { White's plan is to play Qf3 and castle long. } 11... Bxd6 12. Qf3 O-O
{ The Black king is safe now. White will try to organize an attack on the kingside, but as we will see this won't materialize. }
13. O-O-O Qc7 { Removing the queen from the open file. } 14. Kb1 Nxb3
{ That bishop is always dangerous, while it also performs defensive duties in solidifying the queenside, so Black eliminates it and finishes development with his next move. }
15. axb3 Bd7
{ Connecting the rooks. Black is now ready for play both in the centre and on the queenside. }
16. g4 Rfe8
{ A nice prophylactic move. It defends against  17.g5  , when Black can play  17...Nd5  and White cannot take twice on  d5  because the bishop on  e3  will be hanging. }
17. Rhg1 Rac8
{ The last piece enters the game. Now Black wants to start pushing ...b5-b4, so White has no other active plan but to push the g-pawn. }
18. g5 Nd5 { This move is possible thanks to the deep 16... Rfe8. } 19. Nxd5
exd5 20. f5 g6
{ It is much safer to stop White from playing g6 than to allow it. } 21. fxg6
hxg6
{ And with ideas like ...Re4, ...Be5-g7 or even ... Bf5  (since c2 is hanging)  Black has an excellent position. }
