1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 8. f4
Nc5 9. e5 Nfd7 10. f5
{ This is a forceful attempt, but Black can safely take the bishop first and then take the pawn on e5. }
10... Nxb3
{ Eliminating the dangerous bishop first is important so as to reduce White's attacking potential. }
11. axb3 dxe5
{ Now the knight on d4 is hanging so White must keep on sacrificing. } 12. Ndb5
{ 12.Nxe6  is harmless , as Black recaptures  12...fxe6  and after  13.Qh5+  goes  13...Ke7  and 14  ...Nf6  if necessary. }
12... exf5
{ Eliminating the threat of fxe6, taking a second pawn and now Black wants to finish development of the kingside with ...Bb4 and ...O-O. }
13. Be3
{ This creates the threat of Nd5, which wasn't possible previously due to a check on h4 and then on e4. }
13... f4
{ Pushing the bishop further back and also removing the pawn from f5 so that it doesn't hang when White gives check with Nd6+. }
14. Bf2 Bb4 { If Black castles the game is over, so White must give check. }
15. Nd6+ Ke7
{ Now we see the idea of 13... f4, as there is no pawn on f5 to take for White. }
16. Nc4 Nf6 { Offering an exchange of queens that White cannot accept. } 17.
Qe2 Re8
{ Indirectly defending the pawn on e5 and preparing the king's retreat to f8. Once consolidated Black will have a winning position. }
