[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English Attack 6. Be3"]
[Black "44. The English Attack 6. Be3 - 9... h5 10. O-O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3
{ Please note that the move  6.f3  does not have an independent value since after  6...e5  7.Nb3  Be6  8.Be3  Be7  the line will transpose to the main line of the English Attack. }
6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7
{ It is extremely important to start with this move. The point is that in the lines where White plays h3 and tries to play f4  (or Qf3 and g4)  then the bishop on c8 has the option to go to b7. Additionally, this move-order effectively eliminates the lines with early f4 that White may try against 7... Be6, for example   7...Be6  8.f4. }
8. f3 Be6 { The normal developing move, controlling d5. } 9. Qd2
{ Note that White is forced to play this move as the immediate  9.g4  is met by  9...d5  and Black is already better. }
9... h5
{ This move, aimed at stopping White's kingside expansion by g4, is one of the latest strategical discoveries in the Najdorf. It became popular in the late 1990s and it remains a topical variation ever since. Now White needs to decide where to castle. }
10. O-O-O
{ This is apparently the most ambitious approach. The other two moves indicate that White will most likely castle short. }
10... Nbd7
{ Finishing development. In these positions White is forced to jump to d5 sooner or later so that is what Black should be expecting at any point. }
11. Kb1
{ A generally useful move that is almost always played in these positions. Jumping to  d5  is premature , as after  11.Nd5  Nxd5  12.exd5  Bf5  13.Bd3  (the bishop on f5 is very active so White is forced to exchange it)  13...Bxd3  14.Qxd3  Black has the very important  14...Bg5  , exchanging his passive bishop with great play. }
11... b5
{ Black expands on the queenside. His general plan is to play ...Nb6  (most likely after ...Qc7 first)  , in order to control the d5-square and perhaps threaten ...b4  (not allowing White's Na4)  or ...Nc4. }
12. h3
{ This move covers the g4-square in order to enable the f4-push or perhaps to aid the g4-push if White solves the problem of the undefended rook on h1. The f4-push is White's most dangerous plan in these positions where the typical attack by g4-g5 is prevented by ...h5. }
12... Qc7
{ A useful move. The queen is removed from the d-file so now Black can play  ...Nb6.  It is worth noting that the immediate  12...Nb6  would be met by  13.Qf2  , which not only attacks the knight on  b6  but also liberates the d-file for the rook on  d1  , thus threatening  Nc5.  Now if Black prevents both by  13...Nfd7  then  14.f4  is very unpleasant , with a strong initiative for White. }
13. f4
{ Since the attack with  g4  is difficult to organise White often resorts to  f4  in this line of the English Attack. Another typical move ,  13.Bd3  would be bad here because after  13...b4  White is forced to go to  e2  with the knight and after  14.Ne2  a5  Black's attack on the queenside is rolling while White's pieces are stepping on each other's toes.   If White jumps to  d5  ,  13.Nd5  , then as we've seen before  13...Bxd5  14.exd5  Nb6  forces White to take on  b6  since the d5-pawn is hanging. The loss of tempo  (...Qc7 first and then ...Qb6)  (doesn't matter since the extra tempo White has is the pawn on h3, which doesn't make a difference.) }
13... Nb6
{ This was made possible by Black's last move so he plays the move that is common in this line - he controls the d5-square and threatens ...b4, ...Nc4 or ...Na4. }
14. Qf2 Na4
{ A very strong move, immediately attacking the knight on c3 and forcing White to jump to d5. Black intends to put the rook on c8  (instead of just defending the knight by ...Rb8)  and use the e4-square for the other knight to create threats against White's king. This is possible because Black can take on d5 with the bishop, thus leaving the knight on f6 on the board for the jump to e4. }
15. Nd5 Bxd5
{ The knight on f6 is more important than the bishop here as it has access to the e4-square. }
16. exd5 Rc8
{ This increases the pressure on the c-file. Black threatens to jump to e4 and then possibly to give check on c3 with devastating attack. The rook on c8 is necessary as after ...Ne4 the White queen cannot go to e1 as then the pawn on c2 will hang. }
17. Bd3
{ White must control the e4-square, but this allows Black to create a passed pawn. Taking on e5 loses after ...Ne4 and since the only square from where the queen can defend c2 is e2 Black will play the knight fork ...Nac3, winning the queen. }
17... e4 { Winning a tempo and creating a strong passed pawn. } 18. Bf1 h4
{ Fixing the kingside and allowing the maneuver ...Nh5-g3 and then possibly to f5. Black has excellent play in this complex middlegame position. }
*

