[White "The English Attack 6. Be3"]
[Black "45. The English Attack 6. Be3 - 9... h5 10. O-O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3
Be6 9. Qd2 h5 10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. Kb1 b5 12. h3 Qc7 13. f4 Nb6 14. f5
{ This is harmless. } 14... Bd7
{ The bishop calmly retreats, leaving the c4-square for the knight on b6 as the bishop will be re-routed to c6 from where it will attack the weakened  (by the advance of the f-pawn)  pawn on e4. }
15. Qf2 Rb8
{ Black is in no hurry to jump with the knight on b6 anywhere and keeps his options open  (it can go also to a4)  . If you compare this line to the one after the immediate 14 Qf2 the difference is that here Black cannot take on d5 with his bishop, hence the move 15... Rb8 instead of 15... Na4  (which is played in that line but here it would be met by 16 Nd5 when Black would be forced to take with the knight)  . }
16. Qf3 h4
{ An important move as it prevents g4  (which was now possible because the queen on f3 defends the rook on h1)  . Black will now continue with ...Bc6 and then either ...b4 or a knight jump to a4 or c4. }
