[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3
Be6 9. Qd2 h5 10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. Kb1 b5 12. g3
{ This is a typical move in the 8... h5 line of the English Attack. It prepares f4  (so that White can recapture with a pawn)  and also in some lines liberates the way to h3 for the bishop on f1. }
12... O-O
{ Black finishes development and is in fact better prepared for active play - he threatens ...b4 or ...Nb6 and White is unexpectedly under pressure here. }
13. Nd5
{ White can try  13.f4  but after  13...Qc7  he doesn't have direct threats while Black is ready to push  ...b4  or play  ...Rfc8  and continue with queenside play. Against  f5  there is always  ...Bc4. }
13... Bxd5
{ The same idea as after the immediate 12. Nd5: taking with a bishop to gain a tempo by attacking the d5-pawn with ...Nb6. }
14. exd5 Nb6 { The pawn is attacked so White must take the knight. } 15. Bxb6
Qxb6 16. Na5 Rac8
{ Black is ready to counter  17.Nc6  by  17...Nxd5  or otherwise to play  ...Rc5  , attacking the d5-pawn. He is at least equal here. }
