[White "The English Attack 6. Be3"]
[Black "47. The English Attack 6. Be3 - 9... h5 10. O-O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3
Be6 9. Qd2 h5 10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. Kb1 b5 12. Nd5
{ This is the most commonly played move, White jumps to d5 before Black can control that square with ... Nb6, but it's rather harmless as it leads to a good endgame for Black. }
12... Bxd5
{ This is obligatory now , as taking with the knight would allow to play Na5-c6 after  12...Nxd5  13.exd5  Bf5. }
13. exd5 Nb6 { Attacking the d5-pawn, so White is forced to take the knight. }
14. Bxb6 Qxb6 15. Na5 Rc8
{ Not only putting the rook on the open file, but also threatening to play ...Rc5, again attacking the d5-pawn. Additionally, Black defends against the possible invasion on c6. }
16. Nc6 Nxd5
{ Now we see the defensive idea behind 15... Rc8 - the knight on c6 is attacked twice. In order not to remain a pawn down White is forced to take on e7 now. }
17. Nxe7 Nxe7 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 Nc6
{ With an equal endgame. Black will play ...Ke7 and ...Rhd8 and will aim to push his central pawns. }
