[Black "48. The English Attack 6. Be3 - 9... h5 10. O-O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3
Be6 9. Qd2 h5 10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. Kb1 b5 12. f4
{ This immediate push is possible, but it forces White to be careful about ...Ng4 or ...Ne4 ideas. }
12... Qc7
{ The typical queen move in these positions is also good here. Black awaits what White intends to do and at the same time prepares ...Nb6  (as we've seen from the other lines the queen move is necessary for the ...Nb6 move as it avoids White's Qf2 which would attack the knight on b6 but also threaten Nc5 when the queen is still on d8)  . }
13. Nd5
{ Using the fact that this move attacks the queen on  c7  White uses the opportunity to play it. Pushing  13.f5  is harmless after  13...Bc4  , followed by  ...Rb8  and then possibly  ...a5. }
13... Bxd5
{ Taking with the bishop wins a tempo and with the knight on f6 still alive Black has active ideas like ...Ng4 and ...Ne4. }
14. exd5 O-O
{ Finishing development. Now Black has many ideas - the knight jumps to e4 and g4, the capture on f4 with the idea to liberate the e5-square for the knight on d7, the push ...e4. White on the other hand doesn't have active ideas and must be on the lookout for all of the above Black ideas. }
15. g3
{ This aims to keep control over the e5-square in case Black takes on f4 so then White can retake with the pawn and continue controlling the e5-square. }
15... Rfe8
{ Another useful move, either in case of ...exf4  (when the e-file will be opened)  or in case of ...e4, when the rook will be behind the passed pawn. }
16. h3 { This controls the g4-square. } 16... Ne4
{ Black finally starts active play in the centre. } 17. Qg2 exf4
{ Black conveniently opens the e-file now that all his pieces are well-positioned. }
18. gxf4 Bf6
{ The bishop is extremely active on the long diagonal. Black has excellent play since all his pieces have come to life. }
