[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English Attack 6. Be3"]
[Black "49. The English Attack 6. Be3 - 9... h5 10. Be2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3
Be6 9. Qd2 h5 10. Be2
{ A sort of a waiting move, but Black's next move is obvious. } 10... Nbd7
{ Finishing development. White is now forced to put a knight on d5 as otherwise Black can play ...b5 and ...Nb6 with rich play. }
11. Nd5
{ Now comes an important decision for Black. Both captures are possible and Black has the following choice: taking with the knight preserves the bishop pair but allows White to play Na5; taking with the bishop gives away the bishop pair but Black can prevent the move Na5 by playing ...a5 himself. }
11... Nxd5
{ This is objectively the better choice, though both captures are possible. Black keeps the bishop pair and allows Na5, but the point is that he has a strong maneuver at his disposal to deal with that knight. }
12. exd5 Bf5 13. Na5
{ If White starts with  13.O-O  Black can also castle and after  13...O-O  14.Na5  Qc8  we would arrive at the same position. }
13... Qc8
{ The start of Black's defensive plan against the annoying knight on a5. } 14.
O-O O-O 15. c3
{ A subtle move that leaves the c4-square available for the knight. Black's defensive idea is shown after the naive  14.c4  as then he plays  14...Bd8 !  waiting for White to play  b4  when he would take on  a5  and obtain an eternal square on  c5  for the knight. }
15... Bg6
{ The bishop retreats in order to liberate the path for the f-pawn. Now there is no point in playing ...Bd8 since the knight can go to c4. }
16. b4 f5
{ Black advances the f-pawn with the threat to push ...f4 and then follow up with ...Nf6 and possibly ...e4. }
17. c4
{ If White attempts to stop Black's  ...f4  by playing  17.f4  himself , then Black should capture  17...exf4  and after  18.Bxf4  Nf6  he has the excellent e4-square for the knight , while the dark-squared bishop can come to  f6  and be very active along the long diagonal. }
17... f4 { Black continues with his plan of central and kingside expansion. }
18. Bf2 Bd8
{ With the already familiar threat to take on a5 and obtain the c5-square for the knight. }
19. Nb3 Nf6
{ Now the threat is to push ...e4. If allowed Black would also like to play ...b6 to slow down White's queenside expansion, hence White's next. }
20. c5 e4 { Black follows through on his idea. } 21. Bd4
{ This is better than  21.Qxf4.  In that case Black replies  21...Nxd5  and then the queen must go back to  d2  , allowing  ...Nf4  with the subsequent capture of the bishop on  e2.  Then Black will have great play in an open position with the bishop pair. White is well-advised not to take the d-pawn as after  22.Qxd6  Bf7  the queen is suddenly short of squares ,  ...Bc7  being the threat. }
21... e3 { Establishing a monster protected passed pawn. } 22. Qb2 h4
{ The idea is to push ...h3 and weaken White's king. If White plays h3 himself then the natural ...Nh5-g3 will create quite some problems for White. }
23. cxd6 b6
{ A very important move, denying White access to the c5-square, thus rendering the knight on b3 rather useless. The doubled d-pawns are not going anywhere, so Black is free to continue with his kingside play. }
24. Rac1 Qf5
{ The queen is also very active now. Black has ideas like ...h3, ...Qg5, or ...Bf7  (in order to take the d5-pawn)  with excellent play in this complex middlegame. }
