[White "The English Attack 6. Be3"]
[Black "50. The English Attack 6. Be3 - 9... h5 10. Nd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3
Be6 9. Qd2 h5 10. Nd5
{ This is the positional approach. Black can now take on d5 with the knight, preserving the bishop pair. }
10... Nxd5
{ If possible, it's preferable to preserve the bishop pair, though it was entirely possible to take with the bishop too. }
11. exd5 Bf5 { The bishop is quite active on f5. } 12. Na5
{ Otherwise Black would have played ...a5 himself. We already saw in the chapter on the positional line with 6. Be2 that Black should play ...a5 and ...b6 before White manages to pin down his queenside with Na5 and b4  (or a4-a5)  . }
12... b6
{ Luckily for Black he still has the knight on b8 to control c6, thus preventing the unpleasant Nc6 jump. }
13. Nc4 Nd7
{ With a great position for Black as he can play ...a5 if necessary to secure his queenside while he has free hands to play on the kingside and in the centre. He has a lot of ideas: he can push ...h4, he can castle and try for ...e4, he can drop the bishop on g6 and push ...f5, he can put the knight on c5, the bishop on f6  (and then try to open it by pushing ...e4)  . The existence of so many promising ideas mean that Black's position is reliable and also quite easy to play. }
