[White "The English Attack 6. Be3"]
[Black "51. The English Attack 6. Be3 - 8. h3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. h3
{ This became very popular against Black's 7... Be6, but with 7... Be7 instead Black easily defuses White's attempts. }
8... O-O
{ As we already mentioned, White's plan is to push either f4 or g4  (after Qf3)  so it's best to keep the bishop on c8, maintaining flexibility. }
9. g4 Be6
{ Now that f4 isn't an option for White anymore the bishop comes out to e6 so that in case of g5 the knight can drop back to d7 without blocking it while at the same time maintaining control over the important d5-square. }
10. Qf3
{ This is an alternative, but Black obtains great play with the typical move of the a-pawn that aims to harass the knight on b3. }
10... a5
{ This is a very important idea in the English Attack - the a-pawn threatens to come to a4 to chase away the knight from b3. Then Black will have ideas like ...Ra5  (to support ...d5)  or ...Qa5. If White stops the pawn from reaching a4 by playing a4 himself, then Black obtains the b4-square for his knight on b8. From there it will control d5 and will be quite a nuisance to White. }
11. Bb5 { The only way not to allow ...a4 that doesn't weaken b4. } 11... Na6
{ Another important move. Since the bishop on b5 is a good piece, preventing ...a4, Black threatens to chase it away  (or exchange it)  by playing ...Nc7. From c7 the knight also controls the ever-important d5-square. }
12. O-O-O Nc7 { If allowed Black will take on b5. } 13. Bb6
{ If White retreats the bishop to e2 then Black can remove the queen from the d-file to c8 and then start his queenside attack by ...b5. }
13... Nd7
{ Attacking the bishop on b6 and forcing White to part with one of his bishops. }
14. Bxc7 Qxc7 15. a4
{ White finally plays this move in order to establish a firm grip over the light squares on the queenside and thus ensure against an attack on his king. }
15... Nb6
{ Black continues his queenside play. Now he has ideas like ...Rfc8, jumping to c4, putting a bishop on c4 and also  (after ...Rfc8 had been played)  even sacrificing on a4 with the idea of ...b5 next, followed by ...a4. Having so many active ideas means that Black's position is very promising. }
