O-O 9. g4 Be6 10. g5 Nfd7
{ The only reasonable move for Black as e8 isn't really an option. } 11. h4 a5
{ As in the line 10. Qf3 a5 we again see the idea to harass the knight on b3. }
12. a3
{ This prevents the Black a-pawn to reach a3 and weaken White's dark squares on the queenside. }
12... Nc6
{ Keeping the option to play ...a4 at any moment that he finds appropriate, Black finishes development. The knight on c6 can jump to d4 after the knight from b3 is chased away. Another idea for Black is to play ...Nc5 after the White knight is forced to leave b3. }
13. Nd5 a4
{ Being fully mobilized Black starts active play by first kicking the knight on b3. }
14. Nd2 Nc5
{ The knight from c5 exerts pressure on White's centre. White still needs to finish development and he lacks safe haven for his king. }
15. Bc4 { Adding support to the centralized knight. } 15... Rb8
{ Intending to push ...b5 and possibly ...b4. The position is very complex and unbalanced. Apart from the ideas we already mentioned, a very important  (and perhaps somewhat surprising)  idea to have in mind for Black here is the move ...f6 or ...f5, trying to open the f-file and obtain activity on the kingside as well. }
