1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. h3
O-O 9. Qf3 b5
{ This is already great for Black, he threatens ...b4 and ...Bb7, hitting the e4-pawn. }
10. a3
{ A sad necessity for White and a clear indication that his opening set-up has been a failure. }
10... Nbd7
{ A precise move. The automatic  10...Bb7  allows  11.g4  and then the knight on  b8  cannot be developed to  d7  since that would take away the square from the knight on  f6.   With  10...Nbd7  Black is ready to meet  11.g4  with  11...Nb6  and then safely drop the knight back from  f6  to  d7  in case of  g5. }
11. g4 Nb6
{ Liberating d7 for the knight on f6 in case it is attacked and establishing extra control over d5. Black now wants to finish development by ...Bb7, ...Qc7 and start his queenside play by ...Nc4. }
