1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bc4
Be6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Ng5 Qd7 11. Qf3 d5 12. O-O-O d4 13. Qh3
{ This can lead to a curious repetition after } 13... Nc6
{ Finishing development. Note that it is White who is under pressure here to create something as the long-term prospects are in Black's favour - he has a strong centre and space advantage. The pawn on e6 controls the important d5 and f5 squares while White's main problem is the bishop on e3 not having any squares. }
