1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bc4
Be6 9. Bb3 Nbd7
{ This is the idea behind the early ...Be6 - Black doesn't need to castle and can finish development first. }
10. O-O
{ If White takes on e6 and plays Ng5 Black will defend first by ...Nf8 before chasing the knight away by ...h6. If he plays Ng5 immediately then Black will take on b3 and play ...b5. }
10... Rc8
{ Black is still saving a tempo on castling so that he is fully mobilized on the queenside. }
11. Nh4
{ An attempt to make use of the f5-square. Otherwise Black will finally castle and push ...b5  (though be careful not to castle and fall for Bxe6 followed by Ng5)  . }
11... Nc5 { Black is counterattacking White's centre. } 12. Nf5 Bxf5
{ The knight has to be taken. } 13. exf5 Nxb3
{ After the disappearance of the bishop on e6 the bishop on b3 is very strong, so Black eliminates it immediately. }
14. axb3 Qd7 { Attacking the exposed pawn on f5. } 15. Qd3 d5
{ Black can easily get the better position here, so White must be very precise. }
16. Bg5 e4 { Putting the pawns on the colour opposite of his own bishop. } 17.
Qh3 Qc6 { Moving away from the sensitive d-file. } 18. Rad1 Rd8
{ Defending d5 and preparing ...d4. Black has great play here. } *

