[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Aggressive 6. Bg5"]
[Black "59. The Aggressive 6. Bg5 - 9. a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6
{ This has always been the main move. Against the most aggressive attempt against the Najdorf we will be following in the footsteps of Vachier-Lagrave and his resurrection of the 'improved' Poisoned Pawn variation with the move 7... h6 inserted. This line is the most theoretically heavy and even though I did my best to be as concise as I could this wasn't always possible, so be prepared for a few long and forcing variations ! }
7. f4
{ This is critical , of course , but sometimes , though rarely , White varies with  7.Qf3. }
7... h6
{ An important move and the first step in the direction of the 'improved' Poisoned Pawn variation. White is forced to retreat since taking on f6 would give away the most important dark-squared bishop for no compensation. }
8. Bh4 Qb6
{ Compared to the normal Poisoned Pawn variation this version has the advantage that with the move ...h6 inserted the lines where White sacrifices the pawn on b2 don't work that well for White anymore. The drawback is that White can avoid sacrificing the pawn on b2 and can gain a tempo on the queen on b6 by playing Bf2. }
9. a3
{ This is the main line. White avoids entering the sharp lines where Black takes on  b2  as they work very well for Black , particularly with the move  ...h6  already played. Please note that White cannot play  9.Nb3  since that would drop the f-pawn after  9...Qe3+  , or after  10.Be2  then  10...Nxe4  11.Nxe4  Qf4  is very strong. }
9... Be7
{ Now both sides will concentrate on finishing development. Black develops the bishop first. }
10. Bf2 Qc7
{ The queen is forced to retreat back to the usual Sicilian square c7, but now Black smoothly finishes development along the usual path. }
11. Qf3 Nbd7
{ The flexible square for the knight, quite typical of the Najdorf. } 12. O-O-O
b5
{ Black shouldn't worry about e5 whenever he can meet it with ...Bb7, attacking White's queen. }
13. g4 Bb7
{ Black finished development and is ready to counter-attack. It's curious that Black has active ideas on the whole board: ...g5 on the kingside, ...d5 in the centre and ...b4 on the queenside. }
14. h4 { The most aggressive move. The threat is g5. } 14... Nc5
{ Attacking e4 and forcing White's next move. } 15. Bd3 d5
{ Black has two options in this position: 15... h5 and 15... d5. The former leads to crazy complications as shown in the alternative line.  The move 15... d5 is the typical Sicilian central break that secures the e4-square for the knight. Play is more positional and Black doesn't risk coming under attack. As we will see, with best play the game transposes to an endgame where chances are equal. }
16. e5 Nfe4 17. Bxe4
{ If White doesn't take and plays  17.Be1  instead then Black castles long ,  17...O-O-O  and follows up with  ...Kb8  and  ...Rc8. }
17... Nxe4 18. Rh3
{ If  18.Be1  now then  18...Qb6  is good since the bishop left the g1-a7 diagonal. Then Black can continue with  ...Rc8-c4. }
18... Rc8
{ Not only automatically putting the rook on the open file, but preparing the maneuver ...Rc4  (in case White moves the bishop to e1 when Black will play ...Qb6, just as in the previous note)  and also ...Qc4 as we will see next. }
19. Qe2 Qc4
{ The endgame is very safe for Black. The rook on c4 will be very active and with the pair of bishops, even in a relatively closed position, he has options to play on the queenside by ...a5-a4 or ...b4 and on the kingside by ...f6 or ...h5. }
20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Qxc4 Rxc4
{ Black is very comfortable. He will put the bishop on d5 and then possibly play ...a5-a4 or ...Kd7 in order to let the rook on h8 join the game. }
