1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4
Qb6 9. Qd2
{ This is the main move in the normal Poisoned Pawn, but here it works well for Black. }
9... Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3
{ Now White has three main moves at his disposal. The good news is that Black has great play everywhere. }
11. e5 { Of the 3 options White has this one is the most critical. } 11... dxe5
{ It's best to take first as the pawn on e5 can sometimes turn out to be weak. }
12. fxe5 Nd5
{ Of the 3 good options Black has here,   12...Nfd7   12...g5  and   12...Nd5  , the last one is the easiest to play as it forces simplifications. }
13. Nxd5 exd5 14. e6
{ The only attempt for White as otherwise Black plays ...Be7 and castles. }
14... Bxe6
{ Taking with the bishop is necessary as it forces the exchange of the centralized knight on d4. }
15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Be2 Be7 { Black is striving for more exchanges. } 17. Bh5+
Kd8 { The only move not to be subjected to a check on the f-file or from b7. }
18. Bxe7+ Qxe7 { Defending b7. } 19. O-O Nd7
{ A key move in this line - the knight defends the king perfectly when it is positioned next to it and it also has great perspectives from d7 - f6, c5 or e5. }
20. Rxb7
{ If White plays  20.Rf7  then Black again plays  20...Qc5+  followed by  ...Rf8  and then  ...Rc8  , finishing development and targeting  c2. }
20... Qc5+ { Getting away from the pin. } 21. Kh1 Rb8
{ Black's play is simple, he's looking for exchanges as the endgames are good for him because he already has a centralized king and White's pawns are easier to attack. }
22. Rxb8+ Nxb8
{ The position is still tense in spite of many pieces being exchanged. Black is at least equal as his king is not in danger, he has good central control and can continue to look for exchanges. }
