fxe6
{ If you compare with the line 9. Qd3 where White plays the same moves, here Black captures on e6 with a pawn while there he takes with a bishop. The reason is that here the bishop on f1 has access to the c4-square so Black keeps the bishop on c8 to have the e6-pawn protected.   In the line with  9.Qd3  Black takes with the bishop because White's bishop cannot come to  c4  since the queen on  d3  is blocking the way. }
13. Bc4
{ White attacks e6, but now Black plays his tactical trick. The game becomes forcing now. }
13... Nxe4
{ One more time we see the usefulness of the ...h6 move that forced White's dark-squared bishop on an unprotected square. }
14. Nxe4 Bxh4+ 15. g3 Bg5
{ Black continues with forcing moves, attacking the queen. This move also has a hidden tactical idea that becomes evident when White takes on g5 and e6. }
16. Nxg5 hxg5 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Bxe6 Qxg3+
{ The only move, but quite an effective one ! The sacrifice is only temporary and it forces a transposition to an endgame as White cannot avoid the checks on h1 and h2. }
19. hxg3 Rxh1+ 20. Ke2 Rh2+ 21. Ke3 Rxd2 22. Kxd2 Ra7
{ Defending the pawn on b7 and threatening to untangle by ...Nd7-c5. } 23. Bd5
Nd7
{ Black could try to play  23...b5  , but after  24.a4  White will regain material or obtain activity.  The knight move is the simplest as after White takes on b7  (with or without the exchange of rooks)  the knight can go to c5. Black will be a pawn up, but since that pawn is the doubled g-pawn the endgame should end in a draw. }
