1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4
Qb6 9. Qd2 Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. Bxf6
{ The positional approach. White loses a tempo, but Black will also lose a tempo to move the h-pawn to h5  (in order to prevent Bh5)  . }
11... gxf6 12. Be2 h5
{ An important move. It is necessary to prevent the positional threat of Bh5. }
13. O-O Qa5
{ The queen is removed from possible attacks by Rb3 and controls the fifth rank. In case of f5 the queen can be comfortable on e5 when the knight on d4 is exchanged for the knight on b8. }
14. Kh1 Nc6
{ A logical move, developing a piece and attempting to exchange the strong centralized knight on d4. White is forced to take. }
15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Qd4 Be7 { The only way to defend both pawns on f6 and d6. }
17. Na4
{ Black is solid in the centre so White tries to take advantage of the b-file and the b6-square. }
17... d5
{ Not only a counter in the centre, but also a move that prepares the exchange-seeking ...Qc5 when the knight leaves the a4-square. It also opens the a3-f8 diagonal from where the queen can defend the bishop on e7. }
18. Nb6 Rb8 19. Nxc8 Rxc8 20. f5 e5
{ Of course, Black should try to keep the centre closed since his king is still there. }
21. Qa7 Kf8
{ Going towards g7. Black wants to defend the bishop with ...Qa3 or ...Re8 and put the king on g7. }
22. Rb7 Re8
{ Black is temporarily tied down to the defence of the bishop, but so is White to the attack along the seventh rank. What is important is that Black's queen is free to roam around. Black wants to take on e4 or a2 or play ...h4-h3 and then possibly ...Rg8. The position is dynamically balanced. }
