1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4
Qb6 9. Qd3
{ This move is another way to sacrifice the b2-pawn. It has the benefit of eyeing the weakened g6-square, but also the drawback of the knight on c3 being tied as it would allow an exchange of queens when the Black queen steps back to a3. }
9... Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. f5
{ The only serious attempt.   11.e5  Nd5 !  (Immediately forcing the exchange of queens, Black doesn't take on e5 since that would open the f-file for White after the exchange of queens.) }
11... Be7 { Black is ready to castle now. } 12. fxe6 Bxe6
{ Black takes with the bishop in order to exchange the centralized knight on d4. This is possible because the bishop on f1 cannot come to c4   as was the case in the line with  9.Qd2  where Black took on  e6  with the pawn , keeping the bishop on  c8  to defend  e6  . }
13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. e5
{ White must be aggressive. In the case of  14.Be2  Black calmly finishes development with  14...Nbd7  and with ideas like  ...Nc5  and  ...O-O  he is even better. }
14... dxe5 15. Bxf6
{ If White gives check on g6 it is important to remember that the king should go to d8, aiming for the safety of the c8-square as the knight from b8 can come to c6, covering it safely. }
15... gxf6
{ Creating a compact pawn mass in the centre. Now the positional threat is to push ...f5, gaining space and taking away the e4-square, thus securing the king by a strong central presence. }
16. Be2 { Again, if a check on g6 comes the king runs to the queenside. } 16...
f5
{ This finally gets rid of the threat of a check from g6 and it also secures Black's kingside. }
17. Bh5+ Kf8 18. O-O Rh7
{ A good defensive move which improves the position of the rook as it can come to g7 and it also covers the important seventh rank - for example now White cannot take on b7 in view of ...Bc5 with check and winning the unprotected rook on b7. }
19. Kh1 Qd6
{ As usual, Black is looking to exchange pieces. The queen returns with a win of tempo to develop the knight. Now we can see the importance of 18... Rh7 as White cannot take on d6 and b7 since the b7-pawn will be defended after Black recaptures the queen by ...Bd6. }
20. Qh3 Nd7
{ Black has finished his development and has a material advantage. White definitely has compensation, but he needs to be inventive in order not to end up without it. Black wants to play ...Nf6 now. }
21. Bg6 Rg7 22. Qxh6 Kg8
{ The position is unclear. Black will play ...Nf6 next and the game can end with a perpetual if White finds the only move not to be worse: }
23. Rf3 Nf6 { Continuing with the plan, now threatening ...Ng4. } 24. Rh3 Kf8
{ Avoiding mate. Now White must take the perpetual. } 25. Qh8+ Rg8
{ Covering with the knight is also possible , it leads to a messy position after  25...Ng8  26.Ne4  Qd8. }
