[Black "74. The 6. f4 Line - 9. Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4
{ This line isn't very popular nowadays. It suits players who like to avoid forcing lines and just obtain comfortable piece play by retreating the knight on f3, put the bishop on d3 or c4 and then take it from there. }
6... e5 { The typical Najdorf push is one of the best options here. } 7. Nf3
Nbd7 { Defending the e5-pawn. } 8. a4
{ This prevents ...b5. If White doesn't play this move Black will definitely use the chance and will play ...b5. }
8... Be7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O exf4
{ As in the line with 9. Bc4 Black first gets rid of the tension on e5 before moving the knight on c5 and liberating the bishop on c8. }
11. Kh1
{ If White takes on  f4  Black will continue the same:  11.Bxf4  Nc5.  The reason why some White players play the king move is that they fear the move 11... Qb6+ if they take on f4 immediately. This would force them to sacrifice the pawn on b2, but for simplicity sake it's better not to pay attention to that sharp line and transpose to the main line by playing 11... Nc5. }
11... Nc5 12. Bxf4 Bg4
{ The key move for Black's set-up against 6 f4. The bishop not only develops, but it also wants to go to g6 via h5, solidifying the kingside and putting pressure on the e4-pawn. }
13. Be3
{ This creates the positional threat of taking on c5 and pushing e5. This means that Black must defend the knight on c5 first before continuing the bishop maneuver to g6. If White plays a queen move, to e1 or d2, then Black again plays ...Rc8 first and then continues the ...Bh5-g6 maneuver. }
13... Rc8 { Defending the knight on c5. } 14. Qd2
{ A move aimed against Black's ...Bh5-g6 maneuver. The point of the queen move is that it liberates the knight on f3, so it is ready to go to d4 and possibly to f5 if Black automatically continues with the bishop maneuver. The move 14 Qe1 has the same idea, so Black is well-advised not to continue with ...Bh5 but to drop back to e6 and follow it up with the ...Ng4-e5 maneuver, just like in the main line. }
14... Be6
{ Since White's idea was to play Nd4-f5, Black drops back to e6 from where he can control the f5-square. This move also liberates the g4-square for the knight on f6 for the ...Ng4-e5 maneuver. }
15. Nd4 Ng4
{ Black is not afraid of the loss of the e6-bishop since then he will recapture with a pawn and the pawn on e6 will cover both d5 and f5. }
16. Bg1 { White cannot afford to lose the important dark-squared bishop. }
16... Ne5
{ Establishing an eternal knight. Black has a very good and solid position. He has the idea to activate the bishop on e7 by playing ...Bg5  (and generally speaking he would like to exchange the dark-squared bishops)  . White cannot jump to f5 now since there is a concrete threat of ...Nexd3 and ...Nb3 winning an exchange. }
