1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 e5 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. a4
Be7 9. Bc4
{ This is an alternative, as now the bishop is more actively placed. } 9... O-O
{ Finishing development and taking care of the king. } 10. O-O exf4
{ Since the bishop on c4 is active Black's simplest plan is to neutralize it. First he gets rid of the tension on e5. }
11. Bxf4 Nc5
{ Now the knight wins a tempo by attacking e4 and liberating the bishop on c8. }
12. Qe2 Be6 { And finally the bishop opposes the active one on c4. } 13. Bxe6
{ If White doesn't take then Black takes on c4 and plays ...Rc8. It is important to know that these structures with a White pawn on e4 and a Black one on d6 are generally very comfortable for Black. }
13... fxe6
{ This move covers both d5 and f5. Now White's only chance to try for something is to push e5, as otherwise Black is very comfortable behind this 'small centre' of pawns on d6 and e6. }
14. e5 Nd5 { This simplifies the position as White is forced to take on d5. }
15. Nxd5 exd5 16. exd6 Bxd6
{ The position is equal. The difference with the usual positions with an isolated queen's pawn is that the f-pawns are missing and this gives the Black knight an excellent square on e4, thus making the position much better for him than the usual ones when White's f-pawn can control the e4-square. }
