[White "The Fianchetto 6. g3"]
[Black "76. The Fianchetto 6. g3 - 7. Nde2, 9. h3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3
{ The fianchetto is always an option for White in the Open Sicilian. It usually leads to calmer, more positional play, even though White certainly has ideas like h3 and g4 with kingside expansion. }
6... e5 { The standard Najdorf reply. } 7. Nde2
{ Traditionally this has been considered the main move, but the two alternatives 7. Nb3 and 7. Nf3 have become relatively popular lately. }
7... Be7
{ Black will finish his kingside development first before deciding what to do with the queenside and the development of the other pieces. }
8. Bg2 O-O
{ While completely natural, this move also has a tactical justification, as we can see in the comments to White's 12th move. }
9. h3
{ This is a more old-fashioned way to play the line. White plans g4, Ng3 with some kingside expansion. }
9... b5 { Black starts his queenside activity immediately. } 10. g4
{ If  10.a3  then Black has the time to comfortably play  10...Nbd7  and then  ...Nb6  and  ...Bb7  with an ideal set-up.  He can control the f5-square by playing ...g6, not fearing anything on the kingside. }
10... b4
{ Forcing White to jump to d5. Black uses the fact that he had already castled to his advantage, as will be seen from the next comment. }
11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5
{ The point of Black's play lies in the fact that White is forced to take with the queen - taking with the pawn runs into ...f5 and Black takes over the initiative - thanks to the early castle Black is ready for the . ..f5 push. }
12... Qc7
{ Black would gladly exchange two rooks for White's queen - the rooks won't have open files to work on. After  13.Qxa8  Nc6  he will continue with  ...Bb7  and in a middlegame position with just one open file for White to use , the queen will be more agile than the two rooks. }
13. Be3 Nd7
{ The most flexible square for the knight, from where it can go to f6, b6 or c5. }
14. O-O Rb8
{ Black is at least equal here - White will have to lose time to remove the queen from the vulnerable d5-square and Black can continue with ...a5, ...Nc5, ...Ba6 with easy queenside play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Fianchetto 6. g3"]
[Black "77. The Fianchetto 6. g3 - 7. Nde2, 9. O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e5 7. Nde2 Be7 8. Bg2
O-O 9. O-O
{ This is how White players are treating the fianchetto line in the Najdorf nowadays. They don't dream of a kingside attack , but rather concentrate on the centre , more particularly the  Nd5  jump. If White tries to stop  ...b5  by playing  9.a4  , then Black's knight from  b8  heads to the weakened b4-square immediately by  9...Nc6  , followed by ...  Nb4  ,  ...Be6  and even  ...d5. }
9... b5 { A standard move, Black wants to fianchetto his bishop. } 10. Nd5
{ This is the modern treatment. } 10... Nxd5
{ By taking on d5 Black will win a tempo by attacking the queen later on. } 11.
Qxd5 Ra7
{ In this position it is not possible to play  11...Qc7  since the queen manages to escape after taking the rook:  12.Qxa8  Nc6  13.Nc3  with the deadly threat of  Nd5.  In the line with 9. h3 this saving move wasn't possible since Black had a pawn on b4. }
12. Be3 Rb7
{ Black doesn't hurry with the bishop coming to e6 - he intends to use the exposed queen to gain tempo with the knight after ...Nd7-f6. }
13. Qd3
{ White retreats before Black can attack the queen. Against the other moves Black plays in the same manner - ...Nd7-f6 and ...Be6. As always in the Najdorf, the control of the d5-square is crucial. }
13... Be6
{ Now that the queen escaped the bishop can come out to e6, threatening ...Bc4, while the knight on b8 will come to d7 and then most likely on f6. }
14. b3 { Preventing ...Bc4. } 14... Nd7
{ As planned, the knight goes to f6 to cover the d5-square. } 15. Nc3 Nf6
{ Black makes sure that if a White knight appears on d5 after taking it only a pawn will take its place  (and not a piece)  . }
16. a4
{ White doesn't have a better plan, but to try something on the queenside. Note that Black cannot push ...b4 in view of Qa6 and the rook on b7 is hanging. }
16... Qb8 { This move defends the rook on b7 and Black now threatens ...b4. }
17. axb5 axb5
{ Black will follow up with ...b4 and then White will have to jump to d5. Black then has a choice: to take on d5 with bishop and play ...Bd8-b6, or to take with a knight and retreat with the bishop back to d7. }
18. Bg5 b4 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Nd5 Bd8
{ Followed by ...Bxd5 and ...Bb6 with an equal position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Fianchetto 6. g3"]
[Black "78. The Fianchetto 6. g3 - 7. Nb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e5 7. Nb3
{ Now play resembles the 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 line, the only difference being that the bishop is fianchettoed on g2. This has the advantage of providing better control over the d5-square, but also the disadvantage of not controlling the f1-a6 diagonal, thus making it easier for Black to push ...b5 or establish a piece on c4. But as the main line shows play is almost the same as in the line 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. a4 Be6 10. Bf3. }
7... Be7
{ Black continues as in the 6. Be2 line. He first castles and then puts a bishop on e6 and a knight on d7. }
8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O
{ If White plays  9.a4  first Black continues along the same lines ,  9...Be6  10.O-O  Nbd7  , which will inevitably transpose to the main line. }
9... Be6 10. Re1
{ White's plan is to play Nd2-f1-e3 and establish a strong control over d5. }
10... Nbd7 11. a4
{ Black was ready to push ...b5 and play ...Nb6, so White is well-advised to prevent it. }
11... Qb8
{ An important move, but one that can easily be remembered in a way of association with the same idea in the line 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. a4 Be6 10. Bf3 Nbd7 11. Re1 Qb8 ! The idea is to activate the bishop via d8 and b6 or a5. If you compare, the position is almost identical, the difference being the position of the bishop on g2 and a pawn on g3  (there White played Be2-f3 and here g3 and Bg2)  . }
12. Nd2
{ If White plays  12.Be3  then Black continues with  12...Rc8  and then  ...Bd8.  Here there is an additional factor favouring Black - with a bishop on  g2  , not controlling the g4-square , Black has the threat of  ...Ng4  , harassing the bishop on  e3. }
12... Bd8 { The threat is to put the bishop on a5. } 13. a5
{ Trying to prevent the bishop from getting to a5, but this allows ...b6, opening up the queenside and still activating the bishop. }
13... b6 14. axb6 Bxb6 { The bishop is very active on the g1-a7 diagonal. } 15.
Nf1 a5
{ Gaining more space on the queenside. All Black's pieces are well-positioned and he's now ready to react to White's plans. }
16. Ne3 Re8
{ A prophylactic move, controlling the e7-square so a knight from f5 or d5 cannot give a check there. }
17. Ncd5 a4 { Fixing the pawn on b2. } 18. Nxb6 Qxb6
{ Black has excellent play - he controls d5, exerts pressure on b2 and makes it difficult for White to create any activity. He can continue with ...Nc5 and put the rook from e8 to c8 or b8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Fianchetto 6. g3"]
[Black "79. The Fianchetto 6. g3 - 7. Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e5 7. Nf3
{ This looks odd at first sight, but it has the idea of Nh4 to attempt to use the f5-square. Another idea of Nh4 is the Ng2-e3 maneuver. }
7... Be7 { Black continues normal development. } 8. Bg2
{ If White plays  8.Nh4  immediately then Black simply castles as  8...O-O  9.Nf5  isn't very good for White in view of  9...Bxf5  10.exf5  d5  when Black is doing quite alright. }
8... O-O
{ With the king tucked away Black will now see how to continue depending on White's next move. }
9. Nh4
{ If  9.O-O  then  9...b5  is natural and good. Then  10.Nh4  can be met by  10...g6  , followed by smooth development after  ...Nbd7  and  ...Bb7. }
9... Bg4
{ This hasn't been played before  (at least not at the moment of writing)  , but it's a nice disruptive move - whichever way White reacts he is worsening his position. }
10. Bf3
{ If the queen moves to d3 then ...Nbd7 will threaten to attack her via ...Nc5. If the knight comes back to f3 then again ...Nbd7, with the idea to play ...b5 and if White prevents it then ...Nc5 is strong, attacking the e4-pawn and forcing White further to worsen his coordination. }
10... Bxf3
{ It is also possible to go back to e6, having forced the awkward Bf3, but this is more forcing and leads to an equal position. }
11. Qxf3 Nc6 { Threatening ...Nd4. } 12. Nf5 Nd4
{ Forcing the exchange of the knight on f5. } 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Ne2 d5
{ This central pawn break liberates Black's play. } 15. e5
{ If White takes on d5 then Black first plays ...Bc5, defending the d4-pawn and only then takes the d5-pawn. }
15... Ne4 16. Nxd4 Bc5
{ Not only attacking the knight, but also liberating the e-file for the rook to attack the e5-pawn. }
17. Be3 Re8
{ Black will capture the e5-pawn and will have excellent piece play. White cannot defend it because if necessary Black has the ...Bb6-c7 maneuver to make sure the pawn falls. }
*

