[White "The Modern 6. h3"]
[Black "80. The Modern 6. h3 - 9. Nde2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3
{ This move became popular in the 1960s when Bobby Fischer used it with great success to combat his own beloved Najdorf. In the 21st century it re-surfaced as one of the most topical lines. }
6... e6
{ One of the rare cases where I don't advocate the typical Najdorf move 6... e5. The reason is that in this line Black can immediately strike in the centre with ...d5. }
7. g4 d5
{ This is the reason for playing 6... e6. Now the character of the game is completely different compared to all the other lines where White gets to attack on the kingside. White has three main options here. }
8. exd5
{ Please note that  8.e5  is harmless in view of  8...Nfd7  when White is forced to defend the pawn by  9.Bf4   9.f4  allows a check with  9...Qh4+  and after  9...Nc6  10.Nxc6  bxc6  Black has excellent play having strengthened the centre and opened the b-file. }
8... Nxd5 9. Nde2
{ The main move. White's idea in these positions is to use his development advantage and pressure along the long diagonal to develop his initiative. }
9... Bb4 { Black develops by limiting the movement of White's pieces. } 10. Bg2
O-O
{ Once the king is safe Black can start solving the problem of his queenside. }
11. O-O Nxc3
{ White was already threatening to take on d5, so Black takes on c3 first. }
12. Nxc3 Qc7
{ Not so much wanting to take on c3, but preparing the development of the knight on c6 followed by ...Bd7. }
13. Qd4
{ Centralizing the queen and played with the idea of Be3 and Qb6, trying to take advantage of Black's slightly weakened dark squares on the queenside. }
13... Nc6 { Continuing the development with a tempo. } 14. Qc4 Bd6
{ The bishop retreats from the vulnerable position to d6, at the same time preventing a possible Bf4. }
15. Be3 Bd7
{ Black finally finished development without weakening his position. } 16. Ne4
Be7 { Of course, the bishop should be preserved. } 17. Rad1 Rac8
{ The rook is removed from the long diagonal and Black is ready for ...b5 and then possibly ...Na5  (or Ne5)  to c4. The position is dynamically balanced. }
