1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e6 7. g4 d5 8. exd5
Nxd5 9. Nde2 Bb4 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O Nxc3 12. Nxc3 Qc7 13. Qf3
{ This is an alternative. White increases the pressure on the long diagonal and threatens Bf4. }
13... Bd6 { Black prevents Bf4. } 14. Be3 Bh2+
{ An important check. Before coming to e5 Black worsens the position of the white king, because on h1 it may run into a check on the long diagonal. }
15. Kh1 Be5
{ The centralized bishop controls both d4 and f4 and also threatens to take on c3. }
16. Rfd1
{ White keeps the rook on a1 in case Black takes twice on c3. Then the rook will come to b1, so White would be controlling both open files. }
16... Nd7
{ Black is not tempted to take the pawn, he prefers to finish development first. The plan is to remove the rook from the long diagonal and then play ...b6. Since White cannot really prevent this Black will successfully solve his opening problems. }
