1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e6 7. g4 d5 8. exd5
Nxd5 9. Bd2 b5
{ This solves the problem of the bishop on c8. Black obtains excellent play. }
10. Bg2
{ If  10.Qe2  instead , with the idea to castle long , Black simply develops the bishop with  10...Bb7  and after  11.O-O-O  he puts the queen on the safe b6-square. }
10... Bb7
{ Once the problem of the c8-bishop is solved Black should be happy. } 11. O-O
Nxc3 { Forcing favourable simplifications. } 12. Bxc3 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 b4
{ This forces the bishop back to e1. } 14. Be1 Qd5+
{ Black centralizes the queen and provokes f3 or a queen exchange there. } 15.
f3 Nc6
{ With complete equality as Black finishes development with a great position. }
