[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e6 7. g4 d5 8. Bg2
{ This is a dangerous move. Black must be very precise in order not to fall under serious pressure since he is behind in development. }
8... Nxe4 { This forces the exchange of knights. } 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. O-O
{ If White retakes the pawn immediately ,  10.Bxe4  , then Black has the strong  10...e5  , forcing the exchange of queens with an equal endgame. }
10... g6
{ This move is very important. The fianchetto does not just secure Black's king against all possible attacks once castled, but it also has the long-term aim to expand in the centre and kingside with ...e5 and ...f5. }
11. Bxe4 Bg7 12. Be3 O-O
{ With the king safe Black will now concentrate on finishing his development. }
13. c3 Nd7
{ This develops the knight and prevents  14.Qb3  in view of  14...Nc5. } 14.
Bg2 { Getting away from possible attack by ...Nc5 or ...f5. } 14... Qc7
{ Black slowly finishes development. The queen move controls the c4-square and possibly prepares the ...Ne5-c4 maneuver. It also removes the queen from the d-file and controls the d6-square. }
15. Qf3 e5 { Chasing away the centralized knight. } 16. Nb3 f5
{ With strong counterplay in the centre and on the kingside. Black has excellent play here as he wants to continue with ...e4 and ...Ne5. }
