1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e6 7. g4 d5 8. Nde2
{ White voluntarily removes the centralized knight and weakens the g1-a7 diagonal in the process. With his next move Black immediately takes advantage of it. }
8... Bc5 { Immediately targeting the vulnerable f2-pawn. } 9. exd5 Qb6
{ Forcing White's next as defending f2 with the rook is just awkward. After ...Nd5 Black has excellent play. }
10. Be3 Bxe3 11. fxe3 Qxe3
{ This leads to an equal endgame. Taking on b2 is also possible, but this is the safer move. }
12. Bg2 { Taking on e6 would only speed up Black's development after ...Be6. }
12... exd5 13. Qd4
{ White tries to play with the initiative as an attempt to obtain compensation for the pawn. In case of  13.Nxd5  Nxd5  14.Qxd5  Nc6  the position is equal. The queen on  e3  is quite annoying for White so he must seek to exchange her , which would lead to a completely equal endgame. }
13... Qxd4 14. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Black cannot prevent White from regaining the pawn, but he doesn't mind that as long as he finishes development. }
15. O-O-O Nxd4 { Winning tempo for the development of the bishop. } 16. Rxd4
Be6
{ Black only needs to castle, so this is high time for White to recuperate the pawn. }
17. g5 Nh5
{ The knight is temporarily on the rim, but the pawn on g5 allows for ...h6 ideas. }
18. Bxd5 { 18.Nxd5  would be met by  18...O-O-O. } 18... Bxd5 19. Nxd5 O-O-O
{ The endgame is equal as Black will play ...h6, which will open the h-file and expose the pawn on h3. The knight on h5 then can easily return to play via f6 or g3. }
