1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h4
{ With White failing to obtain anything promising in the main lines of the Najdorf lately all sorts of moves have been tried. This is one of them. }
6... e5 { The usual Najdorf move works well here. } 7. Nb3 Be6
{ The bishop controls  d5  and Black is already threatening  ...d5.  Note that with a bishop already on  e6  the move  8.Bg5  is met by  8...Nbd7  (now not blocking the bishop on c8)  and Black is ready to recapture on  f6  with a knight. If White then continues with  9.Qd2  Black will play  9...h6  , winning the dark-squared bishop since  10.Be3  can be met by  10...Ng4. }
8. f4 b5
{ Black starts immediate counterplay. This move also liberates the b7-square for the bishop once it is chased away by f5. }
9. f5 Bc8
{ This bishop will be quite comfortable on b7, especially since White's e4-pawn cannot be supported by a pawn anymore and is subject to attack  (also indirectly by ...b4, attacking the defender of the pawn)  . }
10. g4 Bb7 11. Bg2 b4
{ White is now forced to jump to d5 and this eliminates Black's worry of what to do with the knight on f6 in case of g5. }
12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 a5
{ Black plays aggressively on the queenside, threatening ...a4. On the kingside he will play ...Be7, attacking h4 and when White pushes g5 he will further attack White's pawn mass by ...h6. }
14. a3
{ This prevents  14...a4  as after  15.Nd2  Black will be forced to play  15...bxa3  , which would help the rook become active after  16.Rxa3. }
14... Be7 { Attacking h4 and forcing White's next. } 15. g5 h6
{ Attacking White's exposed pawns on g5 and h4. Black has excellent counterplay since White doesn't threaten anything on the kingside as any pawn move there is harmless. On the other side of the board Black will finish development with ...Nd7 and activate the queen by ...Qb6 or ...Qc7. }
