1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a3
{ This has been played by strong players, including the World Champion, but it's a harmless move since it does not put any pressure on Black. Additionally, playing the pawn to a3 means that White is unlikely to attack Black's queenside with a4, thus inviting Black to comfortably play ...b5. }
6... e6
{ This is the simplest as it aims for Black to get the ideal development with the following set-up: the bishops on e7 and b7, the knight on d7 and the queen on c7. }
7. f4 b5 { When possible Black prefers to develop his queenside first. } 8. Bd3
Bb7 9. Qf3 Nbd7
{ Black is going towards his desired set-up of ...Be7 and then either ...Qc7 or ...Rc8 or even both. Once this set-up is achieved Black has active ideas like ...Nb6-c4, ...Nc5 and ...d5 or a combination of all three. }
10. g4
{ This is the most aggressive set-up by White. Now Black moves the d7-knight in order to make room for the one on f6. }
10... Nc5
{ Another typical idea is to play ...g6, as the bishop will be quite effective on g7 and in case of g5 the knight on h5 stops all possible attacks along the h-file. }
11. Be3 Nfd7
{ Black evacuated the kingside and can now concentrate on his queenside play. Bear in mind that the plan with a fianchetto ...g6 and ...Bg7 is still possible. }
12. O-O-O Qa5
{ Threatening ...b4. It's apparent that Black's queenside play is quite concrete, which cannot be said about White's kingside attack. Black has an excellent position. }
