[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Odds and Ends"]
[Black "90. Odds and Ends - 6. Nb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Nb3
{ This is perhaps the most shocking of all White's 6th moves. In many lines of the Sicilian Black wastes a tempo  (with ...Bc5-e7 or ...Qb6-c7)  to chase away the strong centralized knight and here White is removing it voluntarily ! Still, the move contains an important idea, which is to wait for Black's next move and then play according to that information. For example, if Black plays 6... e6 then 7. g4 is possible, and if 6... g6 then we have a Dragon  (even though a rather harmless one with the knight already on b3)  , while after 6... e5 the bishop can come to g5 without stopping on e3 first. }
6... e6
{ This allows g4, but Black also gets his queenside play going rather fast. }
7. g4 b5 8. Bg2 Bb7
{ White threatened 9. e5 so Black develops the bishop on the natural b7-square and prevents the threat. }
9. g5 Nfd7
{ Similarly to the 6. a3 line Black evacuates the knight from f6. On d7 it has many tempting options: b6 and c4, e5 or c5. }
10. a3
{ Otherwise Black would play ...b4. Generally speaking ...b4 should be played as soon as possible as it disrupts the harmony in White's position - the knight on c3 cannot find a good square once kicked away, plus the e4-pawn will be lacking support. }
10... Nc6 11. h4
{ If  11.f4  then  11...h6  is good , immediately attacking the g5-pawn. Black would like to exchange on  g5  and trade the rooks down the h-file as this diminishes White's attacking potential on the kingside. Note that the Black king is quite comfortable on the queenside after long castling. This whole plan works better with a bishop still on  f8  as in this case the g7-pawn and the eighth rank are better protected.   If  11.O-O  then  11...g6  is good , with the idea of  ...h6  - with the g5-pawn fixed there will be no  g6  ideas. }
11... Be7 12. Be3
{ If  12.f4  then  12...Nb6  shows that Black is fully prepared to counterattack. The knight coming to  c4  will be quite annoying for White. Black also has ideas like  ...Rc8  and  ...b4.   Note that now the plan with  12...h6  is less optimal as the bishop is already on  e7  , so after the exchange of rooks White may have some  Qh5   h3  (-h8 ideas.) }
12... Nce5
{ With rich Sicilian play for Black with plethora of ideas: ...Nc4, ...Nb6, ...Rc8, ...Qc7. The Black king will stay in the centre for the time being as Black can decide later what to do - stay in the centre or castle on either side. }
