[White "Odds and Ends"]
[Black "91. Odds and Ends - 6. Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bd3 e5
{ The standard Najdorf move works fine and soon it will lead to a typical Najdorf structure when White jumps to d5 and Black takes with a bishop. }
7. Nde2 Be7 { Black develops normally. } 8. O-O O-O 9. Ng3
{ An alternative is  9.f4  , but after  9...b5  10.a3  Nbd7  intending  ...Nc5  Black has a good game. }
9... Be6
{ The bishop controls both f5 and d5 and now ...d5 is threatened, so White must do something in the centre. }
10. Nd5 Bxd5
{ Taking with a knight allows for a quick f4 by White, so Black takes with a bishop and with his next move severely limits both the knight on g3 and the bishop on d3. }
11. exd5 g6 { Now the knight on g3 won't easily find a useful square. } 12. Bh6
Re8 13. c4 Nbd7
{ We have already seen this structure in many positions in the 6. Be2 line. Black is very solid and his long-term plan is to expand in the centre and kingside by pushing the e- and f-pawns. On the queenside he would ideally like to establish pawns on b6 and a5, defending against a possible c5-break and establishing a strong knight on c5. }
14. b4 { This takes control over c5, thus preventing ...Nc5 and ...a5. } 14...
a5
{ Black forces simplifications on the queenside. These have a prophylactic character as they reduce White's advancing potential there. }
15. a3 axb4
{ Black will exchange the rooks and then will attack White's exposed queenside structure. }
16. axb4 Rxa1 17. Qxa1 b5 { A very strong move, destroying White's phalanx. }
18. cxb5 Nb6
{ With excellent play as d5 falls and the doubled b-pawns are not going anywhere. }
