1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4
{ The idea of this move is similar to the 6. Be2 or 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 lines, only that White hopes to get the bishops to c4 or g5 in one go. }
6... e5 { The usual Najdorf response is quite appropriate even here. } 7. Nf3
Be7 8. Bg5 Be6
{ The typical reaction. White wants to take on f6 and weaken Black's control over d5 so Black immediately brings another piece to control it, at the same time preventing White's idea of Bc4. }
9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Nd5 Nd7
{ The most flexible square for the knight from where it can come to f6 or b6, controlling d5. }
11. Bc4 Rc8 { Gaining a tempo to bring the rook to the open file. } 12. Qe2 Nb6
{ This move forces White to exchange his active light pieces as the attack on d5 and c4 cannot be contained. }
13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Bxe6 Qxe6
{ The position is completely equal. Black can maneuver the knight back to f6 and double his rooks on the c-file. }
