1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4 e5 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bc4
{ This is an alternative, but it is met in the familiar way with ...Be6. } 8...
Be6
{ As in the line 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bc4 Be6, Black challenges the active bishop on c4 before castling. }
9. Bb3
{ If  9.Qe2  then  9...Qc7  forces  10.Bb3  (taking on e6 is harmless for Black)  and now Black can continue with the harmonious  10...Nbd7. }
9... Nbd7
{ Black doesn't have any problems as he manages to develop in the most harmonious manner. With a knight on d7 he will always have a knight controlling d5  (in case White takes on f6 after Bg5xf6 Black will always recapture with a knight)  and he also has active ideas like ...Nc5. }
10. Bg5 Rc8
{ There is no need to force White to take on f6 since Black is ready for it, so he can make useful moves instead. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 h6
{ When all the useful moves have been played Black can now force White to take on f6. }
13. Bxf6 Nxf6
{ The position is equal. Black can continue with ...Rc6 and ...Qb6 or ...Nd7 with the idea of ...Nc5 or ...Nb6. }
