[Black "97. Odds and Ends - 6. Qe2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Qe2
{ This move has similar ideas to  6.Qd3  in a sense that the typical Najdorf reaction  6...e5  is met by  7.Nf5.  But here things are not ideal for White and Black can in fact play  6...e5. }
6... e5 7. Nf5
{ Going back to b3 would give Black a good version of the English Attack after 7...Be7 and ...b5 since the queen is worse on e2 than on d2. }
7... g6 { The knight is forced to e3 now. } 8. Ne3 Be6
{ White's pieces are pretty awkward so he cannot really use the fact that both his knights control d5. He cannot jump there because after a double exchange a pawn will arrive on d5, which is a typically good position for Black. }
9. g3 { The only way to develop the kingside. } 9... h5
{ An annoying move as it introduces ...h4 ideas - with the pawn on h4 White will have to think whether Black will harass the bishop by ...h3 or will open the h-file by taking on g3. Additionally it allows for the development of the bishop on h6  (since the bishop is defended by the rook)  . }
10. Bg2 Nc6
{ White has problems defending the d4-square where the knight will be comfortable. }
11. Qd3 Rc8
{ The rook belongs to the open file, but it is also a concrete move, as the c2-pawn can hang when Black puts a knight on d4 and White jumps to d5. }
12. O-O Bh6
{ Black has excellent play - his most passive piece, the dark-squared bishop, is active now on h6 and ready to be exchanged for White's good bishop. He has ideas like ...Nd4 and ...h4 and if White jumps to d5 Black will take twice, forcing White to take with a pawn since taking with a queen would lose after Black takes on c1 first and then jumps to d4, threatening a fork on e2  (here the move ...Rc8 comes in handy as after ...Qb6 the move ...Rc5 trapping the queen will be a threat)  . }
