[SetUp "1"]

1. Re1
{ White is preparing the standard maneuver Nd2-f1-e3 to increase control over the d5-square. But Black has a strong maneuver on his own. }
1... Qb8
{ The idea of this move is to allow for the ...Bd8-a5 maneuver. It will activate the bishop and put more pressure on White's centre, attacking the knight on c3. You can also look at this maneuver as a way to fight for the control of the d5-square - by attacking or eliminating a piece that controls that square, the knight on c3, Black is fighting to decrease White's control over that square. }
2. Nd2 Bd8 3. Nf1 Ba5 { Threatening to take on c3. } 4. Bd2 Qc7
{ The queen returns to the natural c7-square. This allows the rooks to be connected, and the queen can also come to c6, controlling d5 and attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. Ne3
{ And now in the game Movsesian-Vachier-Lagrave from Gibraltar 2014 Black missed the following strong move. }
5... Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Nc5
{ This makes it really awkward for White to defend his e4-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Defense of the Queenside"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rqnrk1/1p1nbppp/p2p4/3Pp3/2P5/1N1QB3/PP2BPPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Qd2
{ With this move White prevents the exchange of the dark-squared bishops with ...Bg5, but also threatens Na5 to clamp down Black's queenside and allow for a smooth majority advance by b4 and eventually c5. Black's next move is vital. }
1... b6
{ Whenever possible Black should prevent the moves Na5 or a5 by playing ...b6 or ...a5 himself. This set-up secures Black's queenside and obtains the wonderful c5-square for the knight on d7. The weakness of the light squares on b5 and c6 is very difficult to exploit, while the stability on the queenside allows Black to turn his attention to the centre and the kingside and prepare his play there. }
2. Rac1 a5
{ Stabilizing the queenside and securing the c5-square against b4-attacks. } 3.
Na1 f5
{ Once everything is safe on the queenside Black can prepare his kingside and central play at ease. }
