[SetUp "1"]

1. Na5
{ White is threatening to jump to c6 and then proceed with queenside play with c4, aiming to use the open c-file for his advantage. Black has a tactical defense against this idea. }
1... Rc8 { It is essential to cover the c6-square twice. } 2. Nc6 Nxd5
{ This shows the concept of Black's previous move - the knight on c6 is attacked twice so if White takes on d5 Black will take the knight and will remain a pawn up. Hence White's next move is forced. }
3. Nxe7 Nxe7 4. Qxd6 Qxd6 5. Rxd6 Nc6 { With an equal endgame. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Georgiadis, N.. vs. Mamedyarov, S.."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3
Be6 9. Nd5 Nbd7
{ White doesn't threaten to take on e7 since then the e4-pawn will hang and Black can quickly push ...d5, so Black finishes development. }
10. Qd3 Bxd5 { Since White defended the e4-pawn now Black takes the knight. }
11. exd5 Rc8
{ The first precise move - Mamedyarov prevents White's plan of queenside castling. }
12. c4
{ Now queenside castling is not an option for White as Black will easily open the queenside by ...b5. }
12... O-O 13. O-O Ne8
{ An important move with two ideas  (for now !)  - Black wants to exchange his passive bishop with ...Bg5 and also liberates the path for the f-pawn. Black's play in these positions lies in the centre and on the kingside. }
14. Qd2 { White prevents ...Bg5 and threatens Na5. } 14... b6
{ Of course, Mamedyarov is careful not to allow Na5, which would tie down his queenside. }
15. Rac1 a5
{ Before starting his own kingside play Black stabilizes the queenside. This move secures the c5-square for the knight on d7 and also makes White's queenside advance with b4 much harder. }
16. Na1
{ The idea is to re-route the knight to b5 via c2 and a3. The maneuver is sensible, since the knight was doing nothing on b3, but it's just too slow. What is instructive in this position is to observe how Black's play flows naturally, while quite the opposite is true for White's - in spite of having the bishop pair and a queenside majority he cannot do anything ! }
16... f5
{ Black finally starts his offensive. The threat is ...f4 to trap the bishop on e3. }
17. f3
{ This allows Black to exchange the dark-squared bishops.   17.f4  (This was an alternative, and probably a better one.)  Nef6  (The knight is heading for e4.)  18.Bf3  Nc5  (Now we see how the c5-square comes in handy. Black insists on having a knight on e4. Once it lands there Black will continue with ...Bf6 and may try to activate the bishop by taking on f4, which also allows for ideas of further kingside expansion by ...g5 and ...f4.) }
17... f4 { This would be awful if Black didn't have his next move. } 18. Bf2
Bh4
{ Of course, with all pawns on dark squares it is vital to exchange the dark-squared bishops. }
19. Bd3 Bxf2+ 20. Qxf2 Nc5
{ The knight is stable on c5 from where it controls the light squares e4 and d3. }
21. Bc2 g6
{ Mamedyarov foresees the activation of his knight on e8 via g7 and f5. } 22.
Rfe1 Ng7 23. Be4 Qd7
{ Black prepares ...Nf5 as in the case of a White capture he wants to recapture with the queen. }
24. Nc2
{ The hapless knight finally returns to the game, but where can it go now ? It's only available square is the rim on a3 and then b5, but with all the action happening on the other side of the board it's guaranteed not to take part in any of it. }
24... Nf5 25. b3
{ 25.Bxf5 ?  is bad as after  25...Qxf5  White cannot stop the knight jump to  d3  which would cost him the exchange. }
25... Kh8
{ Black is completely dominating so Mamedyarov takes his time to remove the king from the g-file. The immediate 25 ...g5 was also possible. }
26. Rb1 { White gets away from the fork on d3 and threatens to take on f5. }
26... Ng7
{ Somewhat hesitant play.   The immediate and forceful  26...g5  was very strong.  27.Bxf5  (Apparently this was the idea of White's 26 Rb1)  Qxf5  28.Qe2  (Thanks to his 26th move White manages to avoid losing the exchange and at the same time he prevents ...g4, but that is only temporary.)  Rg8  29.h3  h5  And with  ...g4  coming Black has a decisive attack. }
27. Na3 Nf5
{ Black's position is so good that he can even afford losing two tempi ! But now White gets some counterplay. }
28. Nb5
{ Again, taking on f5 would allow the same attack with ...g5, ...h5 and ...g4. }
28... Rf6
{ Black defends the pawn on d6 so that he can take on f5 with the queen in case White takes Bxf5. }
29. a3 { Preparing b4. } 29... g5
{ Black finally gets his kingside attack going. } 30. Nc3
{ A strange decision , letting the knight come to  d4.  After  30.Bxf5  Qxf5  31.b4  Nd7  Black still has the attack , but at least White has gotten some of his queenside play going. }
30... Nd4 { Of course, now both Black knights are dominating. } 31. b4 axb4 32.
Rxb4
{ White could take with the pawn , though after  32.axb4  Nxe4  33.Nxe4  Rg6  he is unlikely to be able to defend against the impending attack after  ...g4. }
32... g4 { Now Black crashes through. } 33. Qh4 Nxe4 34. Nxe4 Rg6
{ All Black's pieces can be included in the attack so it is impossible for White to defend. The threats are to take on f3 and to win an exchange with ...Nc2. }
35. fxg4
{ This drops the exchange to a fork on c2, but otherwise the threat of gxf3 was even scarier. }
35... Nc2 { And the rest is easy. } 36. Rxb6 Nxe1 37. Nf6 Qg7 38. Rxd6 Rh6 39.
Qxe1 Rxf6
{ A very smooth and strategic victory for Black where it is impossible to determine what White's decisive mistake was. The secret lies in the character of the position after the opening - Black had a plan that was easy to play and follow while White didn't. So Black first secured his queenside and then played on the kingside, advanced the pawns, exchanged his dark-squared bishop and 'simply won' with a direct attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Svidler, Peter vs. Khismatullin, Denis Rimovich"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3
Be6 9. Qd2 h5 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Bf5 12. Be2
{ In the theoretical part I analyze the move 12. Na5, showing that Black can use the fact that the knight is still on b8, covering c6, to play ...b6, chasing away the Na5 from its dominant position. }
12... Nd7
{ Black could have played ...a5, but now we're in the theoretical position from the move-order 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bf5. }
13. O-O
{ 13.Na5  (This would have been perhaps more precise, as the text allows Black the additional option of ...a5.) }
13... O-O
{ But Black just decides to castle and now we have a transposition to the position we considered. }
14. Na5 Qc8
{ This is a strong maneuver that attempts to deal with the annoying knight on a5 by attacking it by ...Bd8. }
15. c4
{ As we saw in the theoretical part it is better for White to play  15.c3  , leaving the c4-square free for the knight. }
15... Bd8 16. Rac1
{ 16.b4  (this would be thematic, but now Black can show his idea.)  Bxa5 !  17.bxa5  Nc5  (securing an eternal square for his knight and cementing the queenside.) }
16... Nc5 { The knight is safe on c5, as b4 can always be met by ...Bxa5. } 17.
Nb3 Bb6 { Of course, Black aims to exchange the dark-squared bishops. } 18.
Nxc5 Bxc5 19. b4 Bxe3+ 20. Qxe3 a5
{ An excellent move. As we see the move ...a5 can be made even after White has played b4. Here it attempts to either open the a-file for the rook on a8, or to fix White's pawns on light squares, which renders White's light-squared bishop very passive. }
21. b5 Qd8
{ Now Black wants to play ...b6, which would make White's c4-pawn fatally weak, so White doesn't have a choice. }
22. c5 dxc5 23. Rxc5 Qd6
{ Black is already slightly better here. He has the better structure and the better bishop. Long-term the endgame favours Black heavily, so White must depend on piece activity in order not to end up strategically lost. Since this was a rapid game the remainder of the game wasn't of the highest quality, even though eventually Black won. What is important here is Black's excellent opening play against one of the world's best Sicilian players. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Anand, V.. vs. Vachier Lagrave, M.."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4
Qb6
{ Vachier-Lagrave is single-handedly responsible for the resurrection of this version of the Poisoned Pawn. }
9. a3
{ The lines with 9. Qd2 or 9. Qd3 where White sacrifices on b2 work really well for Black with the moves ...h6 and Bh4 inserted. For details please check the chapter on the aggressive line 6. Bg5. }
9... Be7 10. Bf2 Qc7 { Both sides finish development in the most natural way. }
11. Qf3 Nbd7 12. O-O-O b5 13. g4 Bb7 14. h4
{ Currently this is White's most promising attempt, though in view of Vachier-Lagrave's games Black is in excellent shape here. }
14... Nc5 { Attacking the pawn on e4 and preparing Black's next move. } 15. Bd3
Nxd3+
{ In the theoretical part I recommend the move  15...d5  here , but Vachier-Lagrave's move is closely related and we can see how the game develops in the similar positions that arise now.   Vachier-Lagrave has also played  15...h5  here and drew a very exciting game with Grischuk in that line. As I argue in the theoretical part I feel that the line with  15...d5  is safer and easier to play for Black than the crazy complications that arise after  ...h5. }
16. Rxd3 d5 17. e5 Ne4
{ Now we have a similar position to the one we get after the immediate 15... d5. }
18. Be1 O-O-O
{ Since the c3-knight is safely defended the move ...Rc8 would make less sense now, so Black makes sure his king is tucked away on b8. }
19. g5 { White can only obtain some play on the kingside. } 19... hxg5
{ Opening the h-file, even though playing ...g6 immediately was possible. } 20.
hxg5 Qb6
{ A typical move in these structures. The queen is activated on the g1-a7 diagonal since White's bishop cannot control it from f2  (where it will be taken by the knight on e4)  . }
21. Nce2
{ Reinforcing the centralized knight and introducing ideas like Bb4. White would want to exchange the dark-squared bishops as his is the more passive one in view of the fact that all his kingside pawns are on dark squares. }
21... Kb8
{ For now White cannot play Bb4 since after the exchange of rooks on h1 Black takes on b4 and wins the exchange after ...Nf2. Black improves the position of the king and liberates c8 for the rook. }
22. Qg2
{ 22.Rxh8  (This would have been thematic, with the idea to exchange the bishops.)  Rxh8  23.Bb4  (But here Black has strong counterplay with the following idea that is good to remember.)  Bxb4  (Note that it was possible to play ...Bd8 and then to try to put the bishop on b6.)  24.axb4  a5 !  (This is how Black creates counterplay on the queenside when the dark-squared bishops are exchanged. Once the b4-pawn is exchanged Black wants to push ...b4 and activate his bishop by ...Ba6.) }
22... g6 { Fixing the kingside and eliminating possible g6 ideas by White. }
23. Rxh8 Rxh8 24. Bb4
{ White is exchanging his passive bishop, but as we already saw Black can create counterplay after this exchange. }
24... Bxb4 25. axb4 a5 { The typical counter. } 26. Rh3 Rc8
{ It's important to keep the rook in order to put more pressure on White's queenside. }
27. Qh2
{ White controls the h-file but it's empty and the main activity is on the other side of the board. }
27... axb4 28. Rh8
{ Anand prophylactically insists on exchanging the remaining rook before Black's counterplay becomes serious. }
28... Qa7
{ The threat is to go to a1 or a2, so after the exchange of rooks White's move is forced. }
29. Rxc8+ Kxc8 30. Kb1
{ The only way to prevent the queen from penetrating, but now Black uses his centralized knight to good effect. }
30... Nd2+ 31. Kc1 Nf1
{ It was possible to put the knight on c4 or e4 as well, as both sides are forced to repeat moves. }
32. Qh8+ Kd7 33. Kb1 Nd2+ 34. Kc1 Ne4 35. Kb1 Nd2+
{ Black cannot try for more since the White queen is quite annoying and there are also ideas based on f5. }
36. Kc1 Ne4 37. Kb1 Nd2+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Naiditsch, A... vs. Carlsen, M..."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Bg2
O-O 9. O-O Be6
{ Carlsen follows our proposed repertoire  (or we follow Carlsen ?)  and finishes development of the queenside first before going for ...b5. }
10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Nd2
{ Naiditsch allows ...b5.   In case of  11.a4  the theoretical part suggests the strong maneuver  11...Qb8  (with the idea of ...Bd8-a5.) }
11... b5 12. Nf1
{ White is following the basic idea of putting a knight on e3 and controlling d5. }
12... Bg4
{ A very instructive move. Its main idea is to disrupt White's harmonious position either by provoking f3  (which weakens White's structure and his control over d5 since the bishop on g2 now is looking at its own pawn on f3)  or by forcing the queen to move, while she has no good squares to go to. }
13. f3 Be6
{ Mission accomplished. Now Black wants to continue with ...Nb6 and ...d5. }
14. Ne3 Rc8
{ Putting the rook on the open file. It was also possible to start with ...Nb6. }
15. a3 { This prevents ...b4. } 15... Nb6
{ Black is harmoniously placed and ready to take over the initiative by pushing ...d5. White's only way to prevent it is to start central play himself, but this further weakens his position. }
16. f4 Re8
{ Carlsen calmly continues to improve his position and doesn't panic at the sight of f5. In that case he will re-route the bishop via d7 to c6 from where it will also control the d5-square, support the ...d5 push, and also attack the vulnerable e4-pawn. This maneuver  (...Re8 followed by ...Bf8)  is a typical consolidating idea in the Sicilian. }
17. Kh1 Bf8
{ It was possible to play in more dynamic fashion by taking on f4 first and then playing ...Bf8, but Carlsen follows his plan. }
18. f5 Bd7 19. Qd3 h6
{ A generally useful move - since everything revolves around the d5-square this move prevents a possible g5 or Bg5, both of which would attack a defender of the vital d5-square, the f6-knight. Still, there was no immediate need for this move and Black could have simply played ...Bc6 immediately. }
20. b3 { White covers the c4-square. } 20... Bc6
{ The natural move, as the bishop is now optimally placed. } 21. Bd2 Qc7
{ Carlsen continues to find ways to improve his position. The queen will come to b7, further increasing control over d5 and one of the rooks may come to d8 to support the d5-push. All this means that at one point White will be forced to jump to d5 and after an exchange there the pawn on e4 will come to d5 with a transformation in the structure. }
22. Rac1 Qb7 23. Ned5
{ White decides that he can't wait anymore. Besides, he doesn't have many useful moves left. }
23... Bxd5
{ Of course, the bishop would be passive if it remains on the board after exd5, so Carlsen gets rid of it. }
24. exd5 Nbd7
{ The knight on b6 served its purpose and Carlsen finds other uses for it - from d7 it can go to c5 or to e5  (after Black pushes ...e4)  . }
25. Nd1 e4
{ A very dynamic and aggressive treatment of the position. It was possible to continue with maneuvers. For example an instructive idea is ...Be7-d8-b6. }
26. Qd4 { Note that White cannot take the e4-pawn in view of the fork on c5. }
26... Ne5
{ A natural follow-up: the knight comes to the liberated e5-square, though again the bishop maneuver ...Be7-d8-b6 merits attention. }
27. Nf2
{ White cracks under the pressure.   27.Nc3  (This is more resilient, though after)  Nf3  28.Bxf3  exf3  (Black still has the initiative due to the over-exposed nature of White's position and his weaker king.) }
27... Nf3 { Forcing the exchange of the king's most important defender. } 28.
Bxf3 exf3 29. c4
{ The only way to defend the d5-pawn, but now Black opens the position and his pieces start to penetrate. }
29... bxc4 30. bxc4 Re5
{ Threatening to take on f5 or to double on the e-file. } 31. Re3
{ 31.Rxe5  dxe5  32.Qxe5  Bxa3  (This is an instructive line showing how White's position falls apart. This can often happen in the Najdorf, as White overextends and when the position is opened Black's compact position and harmonious pieces prove to be well prepared for the counterattack.) }
31... Rxe3
{ It was possible to take on f5, but Carlsen wants to enter on the queenside. }
32. Qxe3 Qb2
{ There are many threats: ...Re8, ...Nd7-c5 or e5, even ...Be7  (as the bishop on d2 is hanging)  . White cannot defend against all of them. }
33. Nd3 Qxa3 34. Qxf3 Qa2
{ Now the d2-bishop and the c4-pawn are attacked and White cannot defend both. }
35. Bc3 Rxc4
{ It was possible to postpone the capture and play ...Nd7, but Carlsen sees no ghosts after his kingside is weakened. }
36. Ra1 Qb3 37. Bxf6 gxf6 38. Kg2
{ This loses, but in the long term White is lost too. He has too many weaknesses: his pieces  (including his king)  are prone to being attacked, and so are his pawns on d5 and f5. Black has a very dangerous passed pawn and once the bishop is activated with ...h5 and ...Bh6 it will be the stronger light piece. }
38... Rc3 39. Rd1 h5 { The bishop finally comes into play. } 40. Kh3 Bh6 41.
Re1
{ This drops a piece, but otherwise White is completely tied down and Black can simply advance the a-pawn. }
41... Rxd3 42. Qxh5 Re3
{ An instructive game by the World Champion. The way he kept improving his position and took over the initiative with 25... e4 is worth studying. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Short, N.. vs. Aronian, L.."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a3
{ Short has played like this before, so Aronian must have been prepared. } 6...
e5
{ Even though our repertoire suggest 6... e6, the positions that arise from this game are very typical for the Najdorf and it is useful to take a look at them to better understand these structures. }
7. Nf3 h6 8. Bc4 Be6
{ The typical move that we see often in the 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 line. } 9. Bxe6
fxe6
{ Now we will explore these structures. They are usually safe and comfortable for Black, since the pawn on e6 covers the vulnerable d5 and f5 squares and Black basically has no weaknesses. }
10. O-O Nbd7
{ When the pawn is on e6 to cover d5 it is also possible to develop the knight to c6, not fearing Nd5, but Aronian intends to put this knight on c5 to put pressure on the e4-pawn. }
11. Ne1
{ Short intends to put the knight on d3. This is not a common square for the knight, but from there it controls c5  (thus preventing ...Nc5)  and supports f4.   11.Nh4  (This is a typical move in these structures when White tries to exploit the weakness of the g6-square.)  Kf7  (It is important to remember that Black can safely play this move, as after ...g5 the knight will be pushed back.) }
11... Be7 12. Nd3 O-O
{ Black finishes development and now threatens to push ...d5. } 13. f4
{ This is the only way for White to create some activity. } 13... Qc7
{ A very strong move which shows that the positions after the exchange on e5, which seemingly leave Black with ugly doubled pawns, are actually quite advantageous for him. }
14. Kh1
{ 14.fxe5  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  dxe5  (This is an instructive line. Now we see the advantages of the doubled pawns - they control all the important squares: f4, f5, d4 and d5. This means that Black can use these squares for his pieces)  (knight, bishop, rook)  (while White cannot, which means his pieces are devoid of good perspectives.) }
14... Qc4
{ Putting pressure on White's position. Now the pawn on e4 is hanging. } 15.
Qe1 Nc5
{ This exchanges the knight on d3, but Black had a stronger possibility.   15...Nh5  (This is more aggressive, forcing White to take on e5.)  16.fxe5  Nxe5  (Black dominating the centre and has phenomenal play. We already saw that if White takes on e5 Black is much better, but leaving the centralised knight on e5 alive doesn't make White's life easier either.) }
16. Nxc5 Qxc5 17. Bd2
{ 17.f5  (This was an alternative, even though after)  exf5  18.Rxf5  Ng4  (Black is still well on top.) }
17... exf4 18. Rxf4 g5
{ Another very strong and instructive move. Black is fighting for the dark squares. }
19. Rf3 Ng4
{ The g4-square is often a useful square for the knight on f6 on its way to e5. Additionally there is the threat of ...Nf2+. }
20. Be3 Nxe3
{ In the Sicilian White's most important light piece is often the dark-squared bishop, so whenever possible Black should try to take it. }
21. Rxe3 Bf6
{ This is a strategically winning position for Black - his bishop dominates the knight as on e5 it will be untouchable, while the knight has no good squares to go to. }
22. Rd1 Be5
{ The ideal square - the bishop defends d6, cements the centre and influences both wings. }
23. Rdd3 Rac8 24. h3 Qb6 { Now Black will probe for weaknesses on both wings. }
25. b4 a5 { Immediately attacking the exposed pawn. } 26. Qd1 axb4 27. axb4 Rf6
{ Of course it was possible to take on b4, but Aronian wants to start attack on the kingside now, correctly assuming that the pawn will not run away. }
28. Ne2 Rcf8 29. Rf3 { Preventing ...Rf1. } 29... Rxf3 30. gxf3 Qf2
{ Now Black switches flanks and viciously attacks the kingside, all thanks to the almighty bishop on e5. }
31. f4 gxf4 { And thus Black has an extra pawn. } 32. Qg1+ Qxg1+ 33. Nxg1 Rc8
{ The rest is just a matter of technique for Aronian. White has too many weaknesses and is already a pawn down, with a second one impossible to defend. }
34. Nf3 Rxc2 35. b5 Rb2 { More pawns will fall. } 36. Nxe5 dxe5 37. Rd8+ Kf7
38. Rd7+ Kf6 39. Rxb7 Rb4 40. b6 Rxe4
{ Now it's already elementary. The Black rook will stand behind White's b-pawn and Black's central pawn mass will advance and win the game. }
41. Rb8 Rb4 42. b7 Kg7
{ Of course , Black is not going to blunder  42...Kf5 ??  43.Rf8+.  He doesn't need the king to win the game as the pawns march forward. }
43. Re8
{ Short doesn't want to wait, so he exchanges his b7-pawn for the e6-pawn, cutting off the Black king in the process. But as before, Black doesn't need the king to win. }
43... Rxb7 44. Rxe6 Rb1+ 45. Kg2 Re1
{ The pawns will automatically win in a way that is worth remembering: the rook is placed on e3, then ... f3, ...e4, then rook on e2, followed by ...f2 and ...e3. This mechanism can be stopped only if the king is placed in front of the pawns, which is what Short does. }
46. Kf3 h5 47. h4 Re3+ 48. Kf2 e4 49. Kf1 f3 { The pawns keep advancing. } 50.
Re5 Kf6 51. Rxh5 Ra3
{ Once the White rook is no longer behind the e-pawn Black moves the rook to allow for ...e3. }
52. Rh8 Kg7 { With ...e3 to follow next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Pikula, Dejan vs. Georgiev, Kiril"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e6 7. g4 d5 8. exd5
Nxd5 9. Nde2 Bb4 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O Nxc3 12. Nxc3 Qc7 13. Qd4 Bd6
{ This is also possible , though in the theoretical part we analyse  13...Nc6  14.Qc4  Bd6  as more precise. }
14. Ne4
{ This is tempting , to win a tempo , but theoretically speaking  14.Be3  is stronger and this is the reason for recommending  13...Nc6. }
14... Be7 15. Be3 Bd7
{ Georgiev uses the fact that the knight is still on b8 to put the bishop on c6 and solve two problems at once - to neutralise White's strong bishop on g2 and to solve the problem of the development of the bishop on c8. }
16. Qb6
{ White's plan is to fix Black's queenside structure and advance on the queenside. }
16... Qxb6 17. Bxb6 Bc6 18. c4
{ It appears that White has an easy, straight-forward play, but please note how Georgiev first neutralises White's advance before activating his own central majority. }
18... Nd7 { First he chases away the annoying bishop. } 19. Bd4 a5
{ A very important move that stops White's queenside play thanks to the excellent control over the dark squares on the queenside, primarily b4. Remember this idea ! }
20. Rfd1 Rfd8
{ Centralisation of the rook, as the other one could be useful on the a-file to support the a-pawn, in case of White playing the bad a3, when Black's ...a4 would fix White's queenside for good. }
21. b3
{ Of course, White understands that he cannot play a3 due to ...a4, but this move further weakens the dark squares and it's clear that he can never push b4 and c5. Putting a pawn on a3 now would force the rook to stay on a1 to defend that pawn. }
21... f6 { Black is slowly starting to advance. } 22. Be3 Ne5
{ An important move ! Black is in no rush to push ...e5, which would weaken the d5-square  (for a possible Nc3-d5 maneuver)  , but tries to use the d3-square for his pieces. }
23. Rxd8+
{ This concedes the d-file, but most likely White miscalculated that he cannot favourably take the a5-pawn on move 25. On the other hand Black was already threatening to come to d3 or even play ...f5, to chase away the centralised knight and then perhaps give check on f3, with the idea to force an exchange there and obtain the bishop pair. }
23... Rxd8 24. Bb6 Rd3 25. Be3
{ 25.Bxa5  this may have been White's idea, but after  Nf3+  26.Bxf3  Rxf3  Black is almost winning - the knight on e4 is hanging and the pawn on h3 will fall. Coupled with the glaring weakness of the long diagonal and the monster bishop on c6 this should be a technically winning position for Black. }
25... a4
{ A good move. As is typical in the Sicilian, Black's two queenside pawns attack White's three in a minority attack, though here the structure is different. }
26. Rb1
{ White tries to avoid the ruin of his structure in case he takes on a4, but now the rook is doomed to stay passive in defence of the pawn on b3. }
26... axb3 27. axb3 f5
{ Finally Black's majority advances. Please note again how Georgiev played - he first took care to stop White's queenside advance, then took over the open d-file to control the position, then weakened White's queenside and finally advanced his own pawn mass. }
28. gxf5 exf5 29. Ng3 Nf3+
{ It was also possible to play 29... g6, limiting the knight on g3. This move wins the bishop pair, but sacrifices the pawn on f5. Black will of course always have more than sufficient compensation in view of White's light-square weaknesses and, besides, White's queenside extra pawn is not going anywhere. }
30. Bxf3 Bxf3 31. Nxf5 Bf6 32. Ng3 Be5
{ The threat is to win a piece by taking on g3. What follows next is a wonderful demonstration of the power of the two bishops in an open position. }
33. Re1 Bc3 34. Rc1 Bb4 35. c5
{ White is desperately trying to reduce material even at the cost of returning the pawn. In case of 35 Rb1  Black could have slowly improved his position by playing ... g6, ...h5, harassing the knight on g3, coupled with the centralisation of his king. }
35... g6 { No rush ! The pawn on b3 won't escape. } 36. Nf1
{ After ...g6 the knight had no prospects, so White tries to re-route it by chasing the bishop on f3 after Nh2. }
36... Rxb3 37. Nh2 Bc6 38. Ng4
{ The knight changed location but it's unclear what it does now, especially after Black's next move. }
38... Bc3
{ Taking control of the long diagonal and again limiting the knight. } 39. Nh6+
Kf8 40. Rd1 Bf6 41. Ng4 Bg7
{ Black can afford to take as much time as he needs as the position is static and his advantage of the bishop pair and better pawn structure is long-term. }
42. Nh2 Ra3
{ Introducing the idea of the exchange of rooks by ...Ra1. After that exchange the king can march to d5 when the pawn on c5 will most likely be lost. }
43. Nf1 Kf7 44. Nd2 Ke6 { Centralising the king and approaching d5. } 45. Kf1
Bb5+ 46. Kg2 Bc6+ 47. Kf1 Ra1 { Following the plan. } 48. Rxa1 Bxa1 49. f3 Bb5+
50. Kf2 Kd5 51. Nb3
{ White somehow managed to get his knight to b3 to defend the c5-pawn, but that knight is far from stable on b3 as it can easily be attacked by Black's light-squared bishop. }
51... Bc3 52. h4 Bd3
{ Now Black's plan is to attack the c5-pawn by ...Bb4 and then attack the Nb3 by ...Bc2, ...Bc4 or ...Kc4. }
53. h5
{ A desperate attempt to divert Black from the described plan, but this only gives Black a passed h-pawn. }
53... gxh5 54. Kg3 Bg6 { Safely defending the passed pawn. } 55. Kf4 h4
{ The passed pawn will force White's king to stay on the kingside. } 56. Kg4
Be1 57. Nd4 h5+ 58. Kh3 Be8 { The threat is ...Bd7+. } 59. Ne2 Kc4
{ Now the king threatens to win a piece by ...Kd3. } 60. Nf4 Bf7
{ The typical restricting move when the bishop limits a knight's movement. }
61. Bg1 Bg3 62. Ne2 Be6+ 63. Kg2 Bc7
{ The h-pawn marches on. A wonderful technical win for Georgiev and a demonstration how these endgames that can arise in the 6 h3 line should be won. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Byrne, Robert Eugene vs. Fischer, Robert James"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is one of the most famous ones in the Sozin Attack in the Najdorf. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 b5
{ Even though this is not our recommended repertoire - where we play 7... Nbd7 -, the ensuing positions that arise are important for understanding the very sharp positional fights that can arise in the Najdorf as a whole. This is not a contradiction, as you will soon see. }
8. f4 Bb7 9. f5 e5 10. Nde2 Nbd7
{ The position has crystallised. White has obtained a clear strategic perspective of play on the light squares  (especially d5)  with a further advance on the kingside  (if possible)  . Fischer himself has won many games on the white side from similar positions. Here he shows what Black should do in these positions. With his last move he connects the knights - so that in case of Bg5 he can re-take with knight and keep control over the d5-square - and liberates the 8th rank for the rook to be developed on the c-file. }
11. Bg5 Be7 { Breaking the pin and threatening to take on e4. } 12. Ng3 Rc8
{ Black's next move was already possible, but Fischer prefers to finish development. In many lines the rook on c8 is threatening the typical Sicilian exchange sacrifice on c3. This sacrifice mainly achieves two major things. Firstly, it destroys White's structure on the queenside, and secondly it weakens White's grip on the central light squares of d5 and e4. Often this may lead to Black either capturing the e4-pawn or pushing ...d5. }
13. O-O
{ Curiously enough, this is bad. But in 1967 it was difficult to even consider Black's next move.   13.Bxf6  was better, though after  13...Nxf6  14.Nh5  (consistently fighting for the light squares by trying to exchange both black knights, but here Black has the typical)  14...Rxc3 !  (with the ideas we described in comment to Black's 12th move.)  15.Nxf6+   15.bxc3  Nxe4  16.Nxg7+  Kf8  17.Nh5  Qb6  is winning for Black, showing the dynamic potential of Black's pieces. After  18.Qe2  Bh4+  19.g3  Bg5  White's position collapses under the attack on the dark squares. Note how the knight on h5 doesn't have a single square to go to.  15...Bxf6  16.bxc3  Bxe4  17.O-O  d5  with wonderful compensation for the exchange. }
13... h5
{ Nowadays this is common knowledge, but imagine the surprise of the players of that age when they saw this move - it was a revelation and only shows how far ahead of his time Fischer was ! In its essence this move is a positional one - it attempts to dislodge the knight on g3 that defends the pawn on e4, thus indirectly fighting for the light squares. Additionally, it prevents the typical exchange with Nh5, which is White's way to fight for the light squares, as we saw in the comment to White's 13th move. Now a tactical skirmish begins, but you can see how the moves of both sides were aimed at achieving positional aims. }
14. h4
{ Physically preventing ...h4, but now Black strikes on the other side of the board. }
14... b4
{ If the knight moves Black will take on e4, so White doesn't have a choice. }
15. Bxf6
{ 15.Nd5  loses after  Nxd5  16.exd5  Bxg5  17.hxg5  Qxg5  and Black is a clear pawn up. }
15... Bxf6 16. Nd5 Bxh4 17. Nxh5
{ White somehow managed to keep the material balance, but he had to give up the dark-squared bishop and allow lines to be opened against his king. }
17... Qg5
{ Black starts the attack. Note that the knight on d5 is not participating in the action - it is pretty there but Black plays around it. Now the knight on h5 is in trouble so White's next move is forced. }
18. f6
{ This secures the g7-square for the knight, but the knight will be stranded there with no way out. }
18... g6 19. Ng7+ Kd8
{ Going to f8 allows the Nf4 trick, but Fischer is careful. } 20. Rf3 Bg3
{ Liberating h4 for the queen. It is incredible how quickly White's king fell under attack while it is Black's king which is 'stuck in the centre !' }
21. Qd3 Bh2+ 22. Kf1 Nc5 23. Rh3
{ White shows a sense of humour, but Fischer will have none of it. } 23... Rh4
{ Not allowing any frivolities.  It was possible to take the queen:   23...Nxd3  24.Rxh8+  Kd7  25.Ba4+  Bc6  26.Nb6+  Kc7  27.Rxc8+  Kxb6  28.Rxc6+  Ka5  29.cxd3  Qe3  and Black wins as the white king is helpless. }
24. Qf3
{ 24.Rxh4  Qxh4  25.Qh3  Qxh3  26.gxh3  Nxb3  27.axb3  Rxc2  is a relatively banal win for Black. }
24... Nxb3
{ Many moves are possible, but note how Fischer remains positionally faithful to the demands of the Najdorf - until the end he fights for the light squares ! He first destroys the bishop on b3, then the knight on d5, forcing White to establish a pawn there - all this we have seen many times in the analysis of our repertoire ! }
25. axb3 Rxh3 26. Qxh3 Bxd5 27. exd5 Qxf6+ 28. Ke1 Qf4
{ With ...Rc2 to come White will be mated soon. } *

